{"title_page": "Erika Alexander", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Erika Alexander\n| image = Erika Alexander.jpg\n| imagesize = 260px\n| caption = Alexander at Comic-Con in 2012\n| birthname = Erika Rose Alexander\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|11|19}} \n| birth_place = [[Winslow, Arizona]], U.S.\n| education = [[Philadelphia High School for Girls]]\n| occupation = Actress, writer, producer, activist\n| yearsactive = 1986\u2013present\n| home_town = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| spouse = {{marriage|Tony Puryear|1997|2017|reason=divorced}} \n| awards = 1996 \u2013 [[NAACP Image Award]]; [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (''Living Single'')<br> 1998 \u2013 [[NAACP Image Award]]; [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (''Living Single'')\n| website = http://www.erikaalexander.com\n}}\n\n'''Erika Rose Alexander''' (born November 19, 1969) is an American actress, writer, producer, entrepreneur and activist best known for her roles as [[List of The Cosby Show characters#Pam Tucker|Pam Tucker]] on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' (1990\u20131992), and Maxine Shaw on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] sitcom ''[[Living Single]]'' (1993\u20131998).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/entertainment-culture/erika-alexander#axzz4oLJpvhF7|title=Erika Alexander on \u2018Get Out\u2019 and Whether or Not a \u2018Living Single\u2019 Reunion Is Really Happening|last=Shaw-King|first=Crystal|date=April 3, 2017|website=EBONY|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 30, 2017}}</ref> She has won numerous awards for her work on ''Living Single'', including two [[NAACP Image Award]]s for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref name=\"Means\">Means, Coleman R. R. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=lCvGBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA134&lpg=PA134&dq=erika+alexander+and+naacp+awards&source=bl&ots=BH6lSq5mWu&sig=7mP8RuzNyQox_lSb-2H3o0SK0j8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixl7Wm2rHVAhXHsFQKHd4lAEUQ6AEIcTAS#v=onepage&q=erika%20alexander%20and%20naacp%20awards&f=false African American Viewers and the Black Situation Comedy: Situating Racial Humor]''. Hoboken: Taylor and Francis, 2014. p. 134.</ref> Her film credits include ''[[The Long Walk Home]]'' (1990), ''[[30 Years to Life]]'' (2001), ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]'' (2006) and ''[[Get Out]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander was born in [[Winslow, Arizona]] and raised in [[Flagstaff, Arizona]] until the age of eleven, when she and her family moved to [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Berry\">Berry, Torriano, and Venise T. Berry, eds. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8NJbCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=erika+alexander+and+actress+and+winslow&source=bl&ots=Kz8XYUHORP&sig=kW0W--bH6l0yMHv-bQuBU-5vt38&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjizYGk8bHVAhULxFQKHZMpCU04ChDoAQg4MAM#v=onepage&q=erika%20alexander%20and%20actress%20and%20winslow&f=false Historical Dictionary of African American Cinema],'' 2015. p. 24.</ref> She is one of six children born to Robert and Sammie Alexander, a school teacher and children's book author. Alexander graduated from [[Philadelphia High School for Girls]].<ref name= faces>Hughes, Mike (August 17, 1995). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/183209661/ 'Living Single' Cast Faces New Shot]\". ''Gannett News Service''. Courier-Post (Camden, New Jersey).</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from high school, Alexander enrolled in a six-week acting class at the New Freedom Theatre.<ref name= faces/> During the fifth week, Alexander got a major role in her first movie.<ref name= faces/> Alexander made her film debut appearing in the independent drama ''[[My Little Girl]]'' in 1986.<ref name= faces/> In 1989, Alexander played the role of [[Hidimbi]] in [[Peter Brook]]'s miniseries [[The Mahabharata (1989 film)|adaptation]] of ''[[The Mahabharata]]''.<ref name= faces/> She got her big break starring opposite [[Whoopi Goldberg]] in the 1990 [[American Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] [[epic film|epic]] drama film ''[[The Long Walk Home]]''. \n\nAlexander performed in a play with Gloria Foster, who then talked about her with her friend, [[Camille Cosby]], husband of [[Bill Cosby]].<ref name= faces/> She later was cast as Pam Tucker on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' starring from 1990 to series finale in 1992. Alexander later went to star in the ABC comedy-drama series ''[[Going to Extremes (TV series)|Going to Extremes]]'', which centered on a group of American students at a medical school on a fictitious Caribbean island named Jantique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1992/tv/reviews/going-to-extremes-1117901570/|title=Going to Extremes|first1=Rick|last1=Marin|first2=Rick|last2=Marin|date=September 1, 1992}}</ref> The series was canceled after one season in 1993.\n\nIn 1993, Alexander began starring as the acid-tongued attorney Maxine Shaw in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Living Single]]'', a role she played for five years to 1998.<ref name=\"McCann\">McCann, Bob. ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television''. Jefferson, N.C: McFarland & Co, 2010.</ref> For this role, she won two [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] in 1996 and 1998. She appeared in [[Toni Braxton]]'s music video for \"[[You're Makin' Me High]]\" in 1996. In 1998, she starred opposite [[Cicely Tyson]] in the CBS miniseries ''[[Mama Flora's Family]]'' based on novel by [[Alex Haley]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7kJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l44DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3511,2289454&dq=mama-flora%27s-family&hl=en|title=Boca Raton News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> and well as appeared in the drama film ''[[54 (film)|54]]''. In 2001, she starred in the comedy film ''[[30 Years to Life]]'' receiving [[Black Reel Awards|Black Reel Award for Best Independent Actress]] for her performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0004697/awards|title=Erika Alexander|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n \nIn 2002, Alexander returned to television playing [[probation]] officer Dee Mulhern in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] drama series ''[[Street Time]]'', which ran for two seasons.  She had a recurring roles in ''[[Judging Amy]]'', ''[[In Plain Sight]]'', ''[[Low Winter Sun (American TV series)|Low Winter Sun]]'' and ''[[Let's Stay Together (TV series)|Let's Stay Together]]''. Alexander also guest-starred on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', ''[[Half and Half]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', ''[[House (TV series)|House]]'', ''[[Suits (American TV series)|Suits]]'' and ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''. From 2012 to 2015, she had a recurring role as Carol Larabee, Mike and Vanessa's neighbor, in the ABC comedy series ''[[Last Man Standing (American TV series)|Last Man Standing]]''. [[Tisha Campbell-Martin]] replaced her in seventh season in this role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/who-plays-the-new-carol-larabee-on-last-man-standing-actress-tisha-campbell-martin-recurs-as-chucks-wife/|title=Who plays the new Carol Larabee on Last Man Standing? Actress Tisha Campbell-Martin recurs as Chuck's wife|date=January 17, 2020|website=Monsters and Critics}}</ref>\n\nAlexander has appeared in a number of films in 2000s and 2010s. In 2006 she played the role of Shanti, a technical science engineer in the science fiction action film ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|Deja Vu]]'' opposite [[Denzel Washington]]. She starred opposite [[Benjamin Bratt]] and [[Jeremy Ray Valdez]]. in the 2009 drama film ''[[La Mission (film)|La Mission]]'', and in 2014 had supporting role in the comedy-drama ''[[Elsa & Fred (2014 film)|Elsa & Fred]]'' starring [[Shirley MacLaine]] and [[Christopher Plummer]]. In 2017 she played Detective Latoya in the critically acclaimed horror film ''[[Get Out]]''.<ref name=\"ebony\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw-King|first1=Crystal|title=Erika Alexander on \u2018Get Out\u2019 and Whether or Not a \u2018Living Single\u2019 Reunion Is Really Happening - EBONY|url=http://www.ebony.com/entertainment-culture/erika-alexander#axzz4oLVCPjdp|website=www.ebony.com}}</ref> In 2012, she is the co-created and co-writen ''Concrete Park'', a science-fiction graphic novel with Tony Puryear.<ref>Brown, Stacia. Clutch Magazine. \"Erika Alexander Co-Writes Graphic with Black Heroine\"</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darkhorse.com/Blog/1676/tony-puryear-and-erika-alexanders-concrete-park-re|title=Tony Puryear And Erika Alexander's Concrete Park Returns With Hardcover And New Series!|website=www.darkhorse.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/news/erika-alexander-develops-graphic-novel-with-black-female-characters/|title=Erika Alexander Develops Graphic Novel with Black Female Characters|website=Essence}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2017, Alexander starred as Constance Irving in the Amazon original drama, ''[[Bosch (TV series)|Bosch]]''. She had a recurring roles in the [[Oprah Winfrey Network]] drama series ''[[Queen Sugar]]'' in 2016 and [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]] fantasy drama ''[[Beyond (American TV series)|Beyond]]'' from 2017 to 2018. In 2018, she was cast in a recurring role as Perenna in the CW superhero series ''[[Black Lightning (TV series)|Black Lightning]]''. In 2019, she received [[NAACP Image Award]] nomination for Outstanding Guest Performance in a Comedy or Drama Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/03/naacp-image-awards-black-panther-1202054744/|title=50th NAACP Image Awards: \u2018Black Panther,\u2019 \u2018black-ish\u2019 Dominate|first1=Tambay|last1=Obenson|first2=Tambay|last2=Obenson|date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Later in 2019, she began starring in the Hulu drama series, ''[[Wu-Tang: An American Saga]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2019/9/4/wu-tang-an-american-saga-erica-alexander-shares-deep-challen.html|title='Wu-Tang: An American Saga': Erica Alexander shares \"deep\" challenges Wu-Tang faced during their early days - Music News - ABC News Radio|website=abcnewsradioonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/wu-tang-an-american-saga-ashton-sanders-shameik-moore-and-erika-alexander-among-6-cast-in-scripted-hulu-drama|title='Wu-Tang: An American Saga': Ashton Sanders, Shameik Moore And Erika Alexander Among 6 Cast In Scripted Hulu Drama|website=shadowandact.com}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe was married to artist/screenwriter Tony Puryear. She actively campaigned for [[Hillary Clinton]] and toured college campuses with [[Chelsea Clinton]], during the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 Democratic Party]] [[primary election|primary]].<ref name=\"Panzar\">Panzar, Javier. \u201c[http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/trailguide/la-na-democratic-convention-2016-live-democrats-count-on-celebrities-to-1469579099-htmlstory.html Democrats Counting on Celebrities to Introduce Heavy Subject Matter].\u201d ''Los Angeles Times'', 27 July 2016. Accessed 30 July 2017.</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[My Little Girl]]''\n|Joan\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[The Mahabharata (1989 film)|The Mahabharata]]''\n|[[Madri]], [[Hidimbi|Hidimbaa]]\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|Long Walk Home}}''\n|Selma Cotter\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]''\n|Rita\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Fathers & Sons (1992 film)|Fathers & Sons]]''\n|Venell\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[54 (film)|54]]''\n|Ciel\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[30 Years to Life]]''\n|Joy\n|[[Black Reel Awards|Black Reel Award for Best Independent Actress]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n|''[[Love Liza]]''\n|Brenda\n|\n|-\n|''[[Full Frontal (film)|Full Frontal]]''\n|Lucy\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''Tricks''\n|Laurel\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''\n|Shanti\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[La Mission (film)|La Mission]]''\n|Lena\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n|''[[Elsa & Fred (2014 film)|Elsa & Fred]]''\n|Laverne\n|\n|-\n|''Secrets of the Magic City''\n|Ms. Fletcher\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Brave New Jersey]]''\n|Helen Holbrook\n|[[Phoenix Film Festival|Phoenix Film Festival Award for Best Ensemble Acting]]\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Get Out]]''\n|Detective Latoya\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[I See You (2019 film)|I See You]]''\n|Lieutenant Moriah Davis\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1986\n|''George Washington II: The Forging of a Nation''\n|Oney\n|TV film\n|-\n|1989\n|''{{sortname|The|Mahabharata|The Mahabharata (1989 film)}}''\n|Madri / Hidimbi\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1990\n|''Common Ground''\n|Cassandra Twymon\n|TV film\n|-\n|''{{sortname|The|Last Best Year}}''\n|Amy\n|TV film\n|-\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Doris Carver\n|Episode: \"Poison Ivy\"\n|-\n|1990\u20131992\n|''{{sortname|The|Cosby Show}}''\n|[[List of The Cosby Show characters#Pam Tucker|Pam Tucker]]\n|Main role (21 episodes)\n|-\n|1992\u20131993\n|''[[Going to Extremes (TV series)|Going to Extremes]]''\n|Cheryl Carter\n|Main role (17 episodes)\n|-\n|1993\u20131998\n|''[[Living Single]]''\n|Maxine \"Max\" Felice Shaw\n|Main role (118 episodes)<br>[[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (1996, 1998)<br>Nomination \u2014 [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (1997)\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Mama Flora's Family]]''\n|Young Flora\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1999\n|''KnitWits Revisited''\n|Amina\n|TV film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2001\n|''[[Judging Amy]]''\n|Fran Winston\n|Recurring role (7 episodes)\n|-\n|''{{sortname|The|Zeta Project}}''\n|Agent Rush (voice)\n|Episodes: \"Ro's Reunion\", \"Absolute Zero\"\n|-\n|2002\u20132003\n|''[[Street Time]]''\n|Dee Mulhern\n|Main role (20 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2004\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|Kema Mabuda\n|Episode: \"Ritual\"\n|-\n|''[[LAX (TV series)|LAX]]''\n|Allison\n|Episode: \"Thanksgiving\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2005\n|''[[Half & Half]]''\n|Maxine Shaw\n|Episode: \"The Big Performance Anxiety Episode\"\n|-\n|''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''\n|Lynn Miles\n|Episode: \"Leaps of Faith\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2006\n|''Sixty Minute Man''\n|Jane\n|TV film\n|-\n|''[[In Justice]]''\n|Alyssa Hill\n|Episode: \"The Ten Percenter\"\n|-\n|''[[Heist (TV series)|Heist]]''\n|Saundra Johnson\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''\n|Vatima Abika\n|Episode: \"No Place to Hide\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2007\n|''[[Side Order of Life]]''\n|Colette\n|Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n|''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n|A.D.A. Kirkson\n|Episode: \"The Case of the Cross-Dressing Carp\"\n|-\n|''[[Numbers (TV series)|Numb3rs]]''\n|U.S. Marshal Tricia Yaegger\n|Episode: \"In Security\"\n|-\n|''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n|Tanya Thorpe\n|Episode: \"Guerillas in the Mist\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Criminal Minds]]''\n|Det. Lynne Henderson\n|Episode: \"The Big Wheel\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[In Plain Sight]]''\n|Theresa Simmons\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[House (TV series)|House]]''\n|Ms. Fields\n|Episode: \"[[Two Stories (House)|Two Stories]]\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n|''[[Suburgatory]]''\n|Gloria\n|Episode: \"The Motherload\"\n|-\n|''[[Suits (U.S. TV series)|Suits]]''\n|Sarah Leighton\n|Episode: \"Discovery\"\n|-\n|2012\u20132015\n|''[[Last Man Standing (U.S. TV series)|Last Man Standing]]''\n|Carol Larabee\n|Recurring role (10 episodes)\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Low Winter Sun]]''\n|Louise \"LC\" Cullen\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n|''[[Let's Stay Together (TV series)|Let's Stay Together]]''\n|Blanche\n|Recurring role (3 episodes)\n|-\n|''[[NCIS: New Orleans]]''\n|Navy Commander Louanne Bates\n|Episode: \"Carrier\"\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''\n|Johanna McKay\n|Episode: \"Crazy Love\"\n|-\n|2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Bosch (TV series)|Bosch]]''\n|Connie Irving\n|Recurring Role (10 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''[[Recovery Road (TV series)|Recovery Road]]''\n|Trish's Mother\n|1 episode\n|-\n|''[[Queen Sugar]]''\n|LeAnne\n|Guest Role (2 episodes)\n|-\n|2017-2018\n|''[[Beyond (2017 TV series)|Beyond]]''\n| Tess Shoemaker\n|Recurring Role (12 episodes)\n|-\n|2018\u2013present\n|''[[Black Lightning (TV series)|Black Lightning]]''\n|Perenna \n|Recurring Role, 8 episodes<br>Nominated \u2014 [[NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Award for  Outstanding Guest Performance in a Comedy or Drama Series]] (2019)\n|-\n|2019\n|'' [[Wu-Tang: An American Saga]]''\n|Linda Diggs\n|Series regular\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0004697|Erika Alexander}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alexander, Erika}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Winslow, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia High School for Girls alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Erika Alexander\n| image = Erika Alexander.jpg\n| imagesize = 260px\n| caption = Alexander at Comic-Con in 2012\n| birthname = Erika Rose Alexander\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|11|19}} \n| birth_place = [[Winslow, Arizona]], U.S.\n| education = [[Philadelphia High School for Girls]]\n| occupation = Actress, writer, producer, activist\n| yearsactive = 1986\u2013present\n| home_town = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| spouse = {{marriage|Tony Puryear|1997|2017|reason=divorced}} \n| awards = 1996 \u2013 [[NAACP Image Award]]; [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (''Living Single'')<br> 1998 \u2013 [[NAACP Image Award]]; [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (''Living Single'')\n| website = http://www.erikaalexander.com\n}}\n\n'''Erika Rose Alexander''' (born November 19, 1969) is an American actress, writer, producer, entrepreneur and activist best known for her roles as [[List of The Cosby Show characters#Pam Tucker|Pam Tucker]] on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' (1990\u20131992), and Maxine Shaw on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] sitcom ''[[Living Single]]'' (1993\u20131998).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/entertainment-culture/erika-alexander#axzz4oLJpvhF7|title=Erika Alexander on \u2018Get Out\u2019 and Whether or Not a \u2018Living Single\u2019 Reunion Is Really Happening|last=Shaw-King|first=Crystal|date=April 3, 2017|website=EBONY|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 30, 2017}}</ref> She has won numerous awards for her work on ''Living Single'', including two [[NAACP Image Award]]s for [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref name=\"Means\">Means, Coleman R. R. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=lCvGBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA134&lpg=PA134&dq=erika+alexander+and+naacp+awards&source=bl&ots=BH6lSq5mWu&sig=7mP8RuzNyQox_lSb-2H3o0SK0j8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixl7Wm2rHVAhXHsFQKHd4lAEUQ6AEIcTAS#v=onepage&q=erika%20alexander%20and%20naacp%20awards&f=false African American Viewers and the Black Situation Comedy: Situating Racial Humor]''. Hoboken: Taylor and Francis, 2014. p. 134.</ref> Her film credits include ''[[The Long Walk Home]]'' (1990), ''[[30 Years to Life]]'' (2001), ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]'' (2006) and ''[[Get Out]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander was born in [[Winslow, Arizona]] and raised in [[Flagstaff, Arizona]] until the age of 11, when she and her family moved to [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Berry\">Berry, Torriano, and Venise T. Berry, eds. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8NJbCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=erika+alexander+and+actress+and+winslow&source=bl&ots=Kz8XYUHORP&sig=kW0W--bH6l0yMHv-bQuBU-5vt38&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjizYGk8bHVAhULxFQKHZMpCU04ChDoAQg4MAM#v=onepage&q=erika%20alexander%20and%20actress%20and%20winslow&f=false Historical Dictionary of African American Cinema],'' 2015. p. 24.</ref> She is one of six children born to Robert and Sammie Alexander, a school teacher and children's book author. Alexander graduated from [[Philadelphia High School for Girls]].<ref name= faces>Hughes, Mike (August 17, 1995). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/183209661/ 'Living Single' Cast Faces New Shot]\". ''Gannett News Service''. Courier-Post (Camden, New Jersey).</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from high school, Alexander enrolled in a six-week acting class at the New Freedom Theatre.<ref name= faces/> During the fifth week, Alexander got a major role in her first movie.<ref name= faces/> Alexander made her film debut appearing in the independent drama ''[[My Little Girl]]'' in 1986.<ref name= faces/> In 1989, Alexander played the role of [[Hidimbi]] in [[Peter Brook]]'s miniseries [[The Mahabharata (1989 film)|adaptation]] of ''[[The Mahabharata]]''.<ref name= faces/> She got her big break starring opposite [[Whoopi Goldberg]] in the 1990 [[American Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] [[epic film|epic]] drama film ''[[The Long Walk Home]]''. \n\nAlexander performed in a play with Gloria Foster, who then talked about her with her friend, [[Camille Cosby]], husband of [[Bill Cosby]].<ref name= faces/> She later was cast as Pam Tucker on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' starring from 1990 to series finale in 1992. Alexander later went to star in the ABC comedy-drama series ''[[Going to Extremes (TV series)|Going to Extremes]]'', which centered on a group of American students at a medical school on a fictitious Caribbean island named Jantique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1992/tv/reviews/going-to-extremes-1117901570/|title=Going to Extremes|first1=Rick|last1=Marin|first2=Rick|last2=Marin|date=September 1, 1992}}</ref> The series was canceled after one season in 1993.\n\nIn 1993, Alexander began starring as the acid-tongued attorney Maxine Shaw in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Living Single]]'', a role she played for five years to 1998.<ref name=\"McCann\">McCann, Bob. ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television''. Jefferson, N.C: McFarland & Co, 2010.</ref> For this role, she won two [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] in 1996 and 1998. She appeared in [[Toni Braxton]]'s music video for \"[[You're Makin' Me High]]\" in 1996. In 1998, she starred opposite [[Cicely Tyson]] in the CBS miniseries ''[[Mama Flora's Family]]'' based on novel by [[Alex Haley]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7kJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l44DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3511,2289454&dq=mama-flora%27s-family&hl=en|title=Boca Raton News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> and well as appeared in the drama film ''[[54 (film)|54]]''. In 2001, she starred in the comedy film ''[[30 Years to Life]]'' receiving [[Black Reel Awards|Black Reel Award for Best Independent Actress]] for her performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0004697/awards|title=Erika Alexander|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n \nIn 2002, Alexander returned to television playing [[probation]] officer Dee Mulhern in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] drama series ''[[Street Time]]'', which ran for two seasons.  She had a recurring roles in ''[[Judging Amy]]'', ''[[In Plain Sight]]'', ''[[Low Winter Sun (American TV series)|Low Winter Sun]]'' and ''[[Let's Stay Together (TV series)|Let's Stay Together]]''. Alexander also guest-starred on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', ''[[Half and Half]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', ''[[House (TV series)|House]]'', ''[[Suits (American TV series)|Suits]]'' and ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''. From 2012 to 2015, she had a recurring role as Carol Larabee, Mike and Vanessa's neighbor, in the ABC comedy series ''[[Last Man Standing (American TV series)|Last Man Standing]]''. [[Tisha Campbell-Martin]] replaced her in seventh season in this role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/who-plays-the-new-carol-larabee-on-last-man-standing-actress-tisha-campbell-martin-recurs-as-chucks-wife/|title=Who plays the new Carol Larabee on Last Man Standing? Actress Tisha Campbell-Martin recurs as Chuck's wife|date=January 17, 2020|website=Monsters and Critics}}</ref>\n\nAlexander has appeared in a number of films in 2000s and 2010s. In 2006 she played the role of Shanti, a technical science engineer in the science fiction action film ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|Deja Vu]]'' opposite [[Denzel Washington]]. She starred opposite [[Benjamin Bratt]] and [[Jeremy Ray Valdez]]. in the 2009 drama film ''[[La Mission (film)|La Mission]]'', and in 2014 had supporting role in the comedy-drama ''[[Elsa & Fred (2014 film)|Elsa & Fred]]'' starring [[Shirley MacLaine]] and [[Christopher Plummer]]. In 2017 she played Detective Latoya in the critically acclaimed horror film ''[[Get Out]]''.<ref name=\"ebony\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw-King|first1=Crystal|title=Erika Alexander on \u2018Get Out\u2019 and Whether or Not a \u2018Living Single\u2019 Reunion Is Really Happening - EBONY|url=http://www.ebony.com/entertainment-culture/erika-alexander#axzz4oLVCPjdp|website=www.ebony.com}}</ref> In 2012, she is the co-created and co-writen ''Concrete Park'', a science-fiction graphic novel with Tony Puryear.<ref>Brown, Stacia. Clutch Magazine. \"Erika Alexander Co-Writes Graphic with Black Heroine\"</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.darkhorse.com/Blog/1676/tony-puryear-and-erika-alexanders-concrete-park-re|title=Tony Puryear And Erika Alexander's Concrete Park Returns With Hardcover And New Series!|website=www.darkhorse.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/news/erika-alexander-develops-graphic-novel-with-black-female-characters/|title=Erika Alexander Develops Graphic Novel with Black Female Characters|website=Essence}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2017, Alexander starred as Constance Irving in the Amazon original drama, ''[[Bosch (TV series)|Bosch]]''. She had a recurring roles in the [[Oprah Winfrey Network]] drama series ''[[Queen Sugar]]'' in 2016 and [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]] fantasy drama ''[[Beyond (American TV series)|Beyond]]'' from 2017 to 2018. In 2018, she was cast in a recurring role as Perenna in the CW superhero series ''[[Black Lightning (TV series)|Black Lightning]]''. In 2019, she received [[NAACP Image Award]] nomination for Outstanding Guest Performance in a Comedy or Drama Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/03/naacp-image-awards-black-panther-1202054744/|title=50th NAACP Image Awards: \u2018Black Panther,\u2019 \u2018black-ish\u2019 Dominate|first1=Tambay|last1=Obenson|first2=Tambay|last2=Obenson|date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Later in 2019, she began starring in the Hulu drama series, ''[[Wu-Tang: An American Saga]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2019/9/4/wu-tang-an-american-saga-erica-alexander-shares-deep-challen.html|title='Wu-Tang: An American Saga': Erica Alexander shares \"deep\" challenges Wu-Tang faced during their early days - Music News - ABC News Radio|website=abcnewsradioonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/wu-tang-an-american-saga-ashton-sanders-shameik-moore-and-erika-alexander-among-6-cast-in-scripted-hulu-drama|title='Wu-Tang: An American Saga': Ashton Sanders, Shameik Moore And Erika Alexander Among 6 Cast In Scripted Hulu Drama|website=shadowandact.com}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe was married to artist/screenwriter Tony Puryear. She actively campaigned for [[Hillary Clinton]] and toured college campuses with [[Chelsea Clinton]], during the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 Democratic Party]] [[primary election|primary]].<ref name=\"Panzar\">Panzar, Javier. \u201c[http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/trailguide/la-na-democratic-convention-2016-live-democrats-count-on-celebrities-to-1469579099-htmlstory.html Democrats Counting on Celebrities to Introduce Heavy Subject Matter].\u201d ''Los Angeles Times'', 27 July 2016. Accessed 30 July 2017.</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[My Little Girl]]''\n|Joan\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[The Mahabharata (1989 film)|The Mahabharata]]''\n|[[Madri]], [[Hidimbi|Hidimbaa]]\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''{{sortname|The|Long Walk Home}}''\n|Selma Cotter\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]''\n|Rita\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Fathers & Sons (1992 film)|Fathers & Sons]]''\n|Venell\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[54 (film)|54]]''\n|Ciel\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[30 Years to Life]]''\n|Joy\n|[[Black Reel Awards|Black Reel Award for Best Independent Actress]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n|''[[Love Liza]]''\n|Brenda\n|\n|-\n|''[[Full Frontal (film)|Full Frontal]]''\n|Lucy\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''Tricks''\n|Laurel\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''\n|Shanti\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[La Mission (film)|La Mission]]''\n|Lena\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n|''[[Elsa & Fred (2014 film)|Elsa & Fred]]''\n|Laverne\n|\n|-\n|''Secrets of the Magic City''\n|Ms. Fletcher\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Brave New Jersey]]''\n|Helen Holbrook\n|[[Phoenix Film Festival|Phoenix Film Festival Award for Best Ensemble Acting]]\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Get Out]]''\n|Detective Latoya\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[I See You (2019 film)|I See You]]''\n|Lieutenant Moriah Davis\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1986\n|''George Washington II: The Forging of a Nation''\n|Oney\n|TV film\n|-\n|1989\n|''{{sortname|The|Mahabharata|The Mahabharata (1989 film)}}''\n|Madri / Hidimbi\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1990\n|''Common Ground''\n|Cassandra Twymon\n|TV film\n|-\n|''{{sortname|The|Last Best Year}}''\n|Amy\n|TV film\n|-\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Doris Carver\n|Episode: \"Poison Ivy\"\n|-\n|1990\u20131992\n|''{{sortname|The|Cosby Show}}''\n|[[List of The Cosby Show characters#Pam Tucker|Pam Tucker]]\n|Main role (21 episodes)\n|-\n|1992\u20131993\n|''[[Going to Extremes (TV series)|Going to Extremes]]''\n|Cheryl Carter\n|Main role (17 episodes)\n|-\n|1993\u20131998\n|''[[Living Single]]''\n|Maxine \"Max\" Felice Shaw\n|Main role (118 episodes)<br>[[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (1996, 1998)<br>Nomination \u2014 [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Comedy Series]] (1997)\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Mama Flora's Family]]''\n|Young Flora\n|TV miniseries\n|-\n|1999\n|''KnitWits Revisited''\n|Amina\n|TV film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2001\n|''[[Judging Amy]]''\n|Fran Winston\n|Recurring role (7 episodes)\n|-\n|''{{sortname|The|Zeta Project}}''\n|Agent Rush (voice)\n|Episodes: \"Ro's Reunion\", \"Absolute Zero\"\n|-\n|2002\u20132003\n|''[[Street Time]]''\n|Dee Mulhern\n|Main role (20 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2004\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|Kema Mabuda\n|Episode: \"Ritual\"\n|-\n|''[[LAX (TV series)|LAX]]''\n|Allison\n|Episode: \"Thanksgiving\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2005\n|''[[Half & Half]]''\n|Maxine Shaw\n|Episode: \"The Big Performance Anxiety Episode\"\n|-\n|''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]''\n|Lynn Miles\n|Episode: \"Leaps of Faith\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2006\n|''Sixty Minute Man''\n|Jane\n|TV film\n|-\n|''[[In Justice]]''\n|Alyssa Hill\n|Episode: \"The Ten Percenter\"\n|-\n|''[[Heist (TV series)|Heist]]''\n|Saundra Johnson\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''\n|Vatima Abika\n|Episode: \"No Place to Hide\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2007\n|''[[Side Order of Life]]''\n|Colette\n|Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n|''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n|A.D.A. Kirkson\n|Episode: \"The Case of the Cross-Dressing Carp\"\n|-\n|''[[Numbers (TV series)|Numb3rs]]''\n|U.S. Marshal Tricia Yaegger\n|Episode: \"In Security\"\n|-\n|''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n|Tanya Thorpe\n|Episode: \"Guerillas in the Mist\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Criminal Minds]]''\n|Det. Lynne Henderson\n|Episode: \"The Big Wheel\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[In Plain Sight]]''\n|Theresa Simmons\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[House (TV series)|House]]''\n|Ms. Fields\n|Episode: \"[[Two Stories (House)|Two Stories]]\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n|''[[Suburgatory]]''\n|Gloria\n|Episode: \"The Motherload\"\n|-\n|''[[Suits (U.S. TV series)|Suits]]''\n|Sarah Leighton\n|Episode: \"Discovery\"\n|-\n|2012\u20132015\n|''[[Last Man Standing (U.S. TV series)|Last Man Standing]]''\n|Carol Larabee\n|Recurring role (10 episodes)\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Low Winter Sun]]''\n|Louise \"LC\" Cullen\n|Recurring role (4 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n|''[[Let's Stay Together (TV series)|Let's Stay Together]]''\n|Blanche\n|Recurring role (3 episodes)\n|-\n|''[[NCIS: New Orleans]]''\n|Navy Commander Louanne Bates\n|Episode: \"Carrier\"\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''\n|Johanna McKay\n|Episode: \"Crazy Love\"\n|-\n|2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Bosch (TV series)|Bosch]]''\n|Connie Irving\n|Recurring Role (10 episodes)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''[[Recovery Road (TV series)|Recovery Road]]''\n|Trish's Mother\n|1 episode\n|-\n|''[[Queen Sugar]]''\n|LeAnne\n|Guest Role (2 episodes)\n|-\n|2017-2018\n|''[[Beyond (2017 TV series)|Beyond]]''\n| Tess Shoemaker\n|Recurring Role (12 episodes)\n|-\n|2018\u2013present\n|''[[Black Lightning (TV series)|Black Lightning]]''\n|Perenna \n|Recurring Role, 8 episodes<br>Nominated \u2014 [[NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Award for  Outstanding Guest Performance in a Comedy or Drama Series]] (2019)\n|-\