ipedia.org/wiki/1964_Stanley_Cup_Finals"}
{"title_page": "Sonic the Hedgehog 2", "text_new": "{{about|the Sega Mega Drive/Genesis game|the Master System and Game Gear game|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (8-bit video game)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Sonic the Hedgehog 2\n|image = Sonic2 European Box.jpg\n|caption = European cover art\n|developer = [[Sega Technical Institute]]\n|publisher = [[Sega]]\n|director = Masaharu Yoshii\n|producer = [[Shinobu Toyoda]]\n|designer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Hirokazu Yasuhara]]|Takahiro Anto|Yutaka Sugano}}\n|artist = {{Unbulleted list|[[Yasushi Yamaguchi]]|Jina Ishiwatari|[[Rieko Kodama]]|Tim Skelly}}\n|programmer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Yuji Naka]]|Bill Willis|Masanobu Yamamoto}}\n|composer = [[Masato Nakamura]]\n|series = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| released    = {{collapsible list|title={{nobold|November 21, 1992}}|\n'''Sega Genesis'''{{Video game release|JP|November 21, 1992|[[North America|NA]]/[[Europe|EU]]|November 24, 1992|AUS|December 1, 1992}}'''iOS''', '''Android'''{{Video game release|WW|December 12, 2013}}'''Windows Phone'''{{Video game release|WW|December 14, 2013}}'''Nintendo 3DS'''{{Video game release|JP|July 22, 2015|WW|October 8, 2015}}'''Nintendo Switch'''{{Video game release|WW|February 13, 2020}}\n}}\n|genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n|platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Sega Genesis]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Windows Phone]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Apple TV]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'''''|\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30d8\u30c3\u30b8\u30db\u30c3\u30b0{{ruby|2|\u30c4\u30fc}}|Sonikku za Hejjihoggu Ts\u016b|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[platform game]] developed and published by [[Sega]] for the [[Sega Genesis]] console, released worldwide in November 1992. It is the second main entry in the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, and introduced [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]]'s sidekick, [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower]], controllable by a second player. In the story, Sonic and Tails must stop series antagonist [[Dr. Ivo Robotnik]] from stealing the [[Chaos Emeralds]] to power his [[space station]], the Death Egg.\n\nDevelopment of the game began in November 1991. The game was developed by both Japanese and American staff at [[Sega Technical Institute]]. The game was directed by Masaharu Yoshii and produced by [[Shinobu Toyoda]], with game design led by [[Hirokazu Yasuhara]] and music composed by [[Masato Nakamura]]. Art director Tim Skelly designed the appearance of the new 3D special stages based on a [[tech demo]] created by [[Yuji Naka]]. The staff increased the speed of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' in comparison to its predecessor.\n\n''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' sold over six million copies, making it the second-bestselling Genesis game behind the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''. Cited as one of the [[greatest video games of all time]], it received acclaim for its level design, visuals and music, although its multiplayer mode was criticized. It has been rereleased on various platforms; a remastered version developed using the [[Retro Engine]] released on [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] in December 2013. Two direct sequels, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' and ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'', were released in 1994.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Aquatic Ruins from Sonic 2 for Mega Drive.png|thumb|left|Sonic and Tails hopping across pillars in the third stage, Aquatic Ruin Zone]]\n''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' is a [[2D computer graphics|2D]] [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game]].<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2007/06/11/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=January 28, 2019 |date=June 11, 2007 |first=Thomas |last=Lucas M. |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis}}</ref> The game stars [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]] and his sidekick, [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower]], who is described as having idolized Sonic as a child and wanting to keep up with him.<ref name=\"m3\">''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 3.</ref> At the game's start, the player can select to either play as Sonic, Tails, or both. The difference between the two is purely cosmetic; the two both have identical abilities.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 8.</ref> In the dual mode, players control Sonic while Tails runs along beside him. A second player can join in at any time and control Tails separately.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 7.</ref> The game takes place over a series of levels, each divided into one, two, or three acts with a [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] fight with Robotnik at the end of the last act. Certain levels have features that are unique to them; for example, Emerald Hill has corkscrew-like loops, and Chemical Plant has boost pads that instantly put Sonic at his top speed.<ref name=\"m3\"/> The character can jump on enemies to defeat them; the game also introduces a new move, the \"spin dash\" or \"Super Dash Attack\", by which the player curls in a ball and spins while stationary, resulting in a speed boost.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 6.</ref> When the player is attacked by an enemy without rings, is crushed, falls off-screen, drowns, or exceeds the act's ten-minute limit, they lose a [[health (gaming)|life]] and return to the start of the act or from the most recently passed [[checkpoint (video gaming)|checkpoint]].<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 9.</ref> Dying with zero lives gives the player a [[game over]].<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 18.</ref>\n\n[[File:Sonic 2 SpecialStage.gif|thumb|right|The game's special stages, in which the player collects rings in hopes of obtaining a Chaos Emerald, are presented in 3D, unlike the rest of the game.]]\n\nWhen the player collects at least 50 rings and passes a checkpoint, they can warp to a \"special stage\".<ref name=stages>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Jared|title=A Guide to 'Sonic The Hedgehog' Version 2.0's Hidden Level-select, Debug Mode, and Many More Secrets|url=http://toucharcade.com/2013/05/27/a-guide-to-sonic-the-hedgehog-version-2-0s-hidden-level-select-debug-mode-and-many-more-secrets/|website=TouchArcade|publisher=[[Arnold Kim]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> In these stages, the player runs through a pseudo-[[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[half-pipe]] course, collecting rings and dodging bombs. A set amount of rings must be collected to pass through each of three checkpoints and in turn to obtain the emerald itself. If Sonic collides with a bomb, he loses ten rings and is immobilized momentarily. The stages rise in difficulty, and the player cannot enter any stage without passing the previous one. After finishing, the player is transported back to the star post they used to enter the special stage, with their ring-count reset to zero.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 17.</ref> When all Emeralds have been collected, Sonic can transform into Super Sonic by collecting 50 rings and jumping.<ref name=gameplay>{{cite web|last1=Creegan|first1=Dermot|title=Casual Monday: Sonic the Hedgehog 2|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2014/10/27/casual-monday-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/114175/|website=Hardcore Gamer|publisher=Disqus|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref name=stages/> Super Sonic is invincible to attacks, runs faster, and jumps further; however, he loses one ring per second and reverts to regular Sonic when his rings are depleted.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\nThe game also has a competitive mode, where two players compete against each other to the finish line, as either Sonic or Tails, in a split-screen race through three of the regular levels and a special stage. After one player finishes one of the regular levels, the other player must finish the zone within 60 seconds, or the level ends instantly. In the regular levels, players are ranked in five areas (score, time, rings held at the end of the level, total rings collected, and the number of item boxes broken). The player with wins in the most number of categories wins the level. In the Special Stage, players compete to obtain the most rings. The mode ends when all stages have been completed, or if a player loses all their lives, in which their opponent will automatically win.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, pp. 19\u201320.</ref>\n\n===''Knuckles the Echidna in Sonic the Hedgehog 2''===\n{{See also|Sonic &amp; Knuckles}}\n''Sonic & Knuckles'' was released in 1994, two years after ''Sonic 2''. The ''Sonic & Knuckles'' [[ROM cartridge|game cartridge]] features a special \"lock-on\" port into which the player can insert other Genesis cartridges. Attaching ''Sonic 2'' unlocks ''Knuckles the Echidna in Sonic the Hedgehog 2'', a variation of ''Sonic 2'' whereby the player plays as [[Knuckles the Echidna]], a character introduced in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' and not playable until ''Sonic & Knuckles''.<ref name=lockon>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic & Knuckles \"lock-on\" review|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/02/sonic_and_knuckles_virtual_console|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-14}}</ref> Though the game is largely identical to ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'', Knuckles is able to glide and climb walls, allowing him access to areas previously inaccessible to Sonic or Tails. However, he cannot jump as high, making some parts of the game, such as certain boss fights, more difficult. In addition, Knuckles restarts with the amount of rings he collected at checkpoints (if he loses a life), the options are unavailable, the special stages have slightly fewer rings required to collect than before (for example, ten rings fewer than in the special stages with Sonic and Tails), and the two-player mode is removed.<ref name=lockon/>\n\n==Plot==\nThe game's premise is similar to that of the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''. Sonic's nemesis, [[Dr. Ivo Robotnik]], is planning world domination through the power of the [[Chaos Emeralds]] and an army of robots powered by trapped animals. Specific to this game, he is additionally constructing an armored space station known as the Death Egg (an homage to the [[Death Star]]), also for the means of world domination.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref>\n\nThe events of the game see Sonic and Tails chasing Robotnik through West Side Island, and eventually up to the Death Egg, pursuing him with Tails' biplane, the Tornado. The plane is damaged after being shot at, but Sonic still manages to infiltrate the Death Egg, alone. Once there, he battles a robotic imposter before taking on Robotnik, who is piloting a giant [[mech]]. Sonic manages to defeat the robot and it explodes, damaging the Death Egg and knocking it out of orbit. Sonic falls to the ground and is saved by Tails in the Tornado. If the player has collected all of the Chaos Emeralds, Sonic, in his [[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)#Super transformation|Super Sonic]] form, flies alongside it.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\n==Development==\nFollowing the release of the original ''Sonic the Hedgehog'', creator [[Yuji Naka]] quit [[Sega]] due to disagreements over corporate policy.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\">{{cite web|last=Horowitz|first=Ken|url=http://www.sega-16.com/2007/06/developers-den-sega-technical-institute/|title=Developer's Den: Sega Technical Institute|work=Sega-16|date=2007-06-11|accessdate=2014-07-11}}</ref><ref name=\"1up.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-sonic|title=The Essential 50 Part 28 - Sonic the Hedgehog|work=[[1UP.com]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523204203/http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-sonic|archivedate=May 23, 2011|accessdate=2014-07-21|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Mark Cerny]], who had recently founded [[Sega Technical Institute]] (STI) in California, met with Naka in Japan and offered him a higher salary and more creative freedom if he joined STI.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"1up.com\"/> Naka agreed, and [[Hirokazu Yasuhara]], the lead level designer of ''Sonic the Hedgehog'', also decided to move to STI.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"1up.com\"/> Yasuhara had been assigned to help Cerny establish STI in 1990, but the outbreak of the [[Gulf War]] delayed his move to the United States by three months, during which he joined [[Sonic Team]] and became part of the original ''Sonic'' project.<ref name=\"Yasuhara\">{{cite magazine|title=Sonic's Architect: GI Interviews Hirokazu Yasuhara|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|issue=124|volume=13|date=August 2003|pages=114\u2013116}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Thomason|first=Steve|title=Birth of a Hedgehog|magazine=[[Nintendo Power]]|issue=211|volume=20|date=January 2007|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|page=72}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of ''Sonic 2'' began in November 1991, two months later than Cerny had intended, as Sega of America initially felt it was too soon for a sequel.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\" /> STI handled development;<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"gibehind\">{{cite web|last1=Shea|first1=Brian|title=The Behind-The-Scenes Story Of How Sonic 2 Became Sega\u2019s Ace In The Hole|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/21/the-behind-the-scenes-story-of-how-sonic-2-became-sega-ace-in-the-hole.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|accessdate=15 March 2018|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wrong\">{{cite web|last1=Shea|first1=Brian|title=Where Sonic Went Wrong|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/11/09/where-sonic-went-wrong.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|accessdate=15 March 2018|date=November 14, 2006}}</ref> both American and Japanese staff contributed, although, according to team member Tim Skelly, \"Everyone attached to ''Sonic 2'' ultimately worked for Yuji Naka. I think Naka would have been much happier if he was working with an all-Japanese team, but just because of the language barrier and some cultural differences.\"<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\" />\n\nSkelly designed the appearance of the pseudo-3D special stages, based on a [[tech demo]] created by Naka.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2SQJ8XeArso|title=G4 Icons Episode #37: Yuji Naka|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2013-04-05|accessdate=2018-03-15}} Event occurs at 8:50.</ref> The special stages were created out of [[Pre-rendering|pre-rendered]] [[3D computer graphics|3D polygons]], video of which was compressed and halved vertically and horizontally to fit in the [[ROM cartridge|game cartridge]].<ref>[http://blogs.sega.com/2015/10/ 3D Sonic The Hedgehog 2 Included in the SEGA 3D Classics], [[Sega]] (October 6, 2015)</ref> ''Sonic 2'' also introduced Sonic's sidekick [[Tails (character)|Tails]], a flying two-tailed fox, inspired by Japanese folklore about the [[kitsune]] and created by level artist [[Yasushi Yamaguchi]]. Sega of America objected to the character's name, Miles Prower (a [[pun]] on \"[[miles per hour]]\"), so he was given the nickname Tails as a compromise.<ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Blake J.|title=Console Wars: Sega, Nintendo, and the Battle That Defined a Generation|year=2014|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-06-227669-8|pages=244\u2013247}}</ref> Masaharu Yoshii served as director. The staff increased the speed of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' compared to the first game.<ref name=\"Sega illustrations\">{{cite book|title=Sega Video Game Illustrations|year=1994|work=Nippon Shuppan Hanbai (Deutschland) GmbH|location= |isbn=3-910052-50-9|page=50}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nLike the previous game, the music was composed by [[Masato Nakamura]], bassist and songwriter of the [[J-pop]] band [[Dreams Come True (band)|Dreams Come True]]. Nakamura began composing early in development with only concept images for reference, taking a similar approach to his method for ''Sonic 1''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=When I started writing the music, \"Sonic the Hedgehog 1\" was just still images...\"Sonic the Hedgehog 2\" started off the kind of the same. Just graphics.}}</ref> Nakamura treated ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' as a film and designed the music around the atmosphere that he felt from the images of the stages.<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=I wanted to treat 'Sonic the Hedgehog' as a film, my inspiration came from each screenshot, or each stage.}}</ref> Except for the graphics and some discussion with Sonic Team, Nakamura was given freedom, which he believes was the reason why he was able to create \"such melodic tunes and unusual rhythm patterns\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=There were some briefs and meetings...otherwise, they let me do as I pleased, and gave me the freedom to create music.}}</ref> Nakamura created the music while he was recording with Dreams Come True in London, working on their fifth album ''[[The Swinging Star]]''. As a gift to Sonic Team, Masato produced an alternate version of the ending theme with Dreams Come True, included on ''The Swinging Star''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Naka|first=Yuji|title=Interview with Yuju Naka|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=Nakamura reoworked the ending theme...info a song entitled \"Sweet Sweet Sweet\" for inclusion on the Dreams Come True album}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the stage music from Chemical Plant and Casino Night Zone were remixed by [[Sega]] for use in ''[[Sonic Generations]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic Colours Soundtrack Racing to iTunes|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2011/01/sonic_colours_soundtrack_racing_to_itunes|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-14}}</ref> That October, a three-disc compilation of the music from ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' and ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' was released in Japan.<ref name=\"musicday\">{{cite web|last1=Elston|first1=Brett|title=Game music of the day: Sonic the Hedgehog 2|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/game-music-of-the-day-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/|website=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=Future US|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It compilation includes comments by Naka and an interview with Nakamura.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gantayat|first1=Anoop|title=TGS 2005: Eyes-On Sonic Next-Gen|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2005/09/17/tgs-2005-eyes-on-sonic-next-gen|website=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=A Look Back at 20 Years of Music History with Sonic|url=http://kotaku.com/5861124/sonic-music-video|website=Kotaku|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> The first disc contains original tracks from both games, and the second contains Nakamura's [[Demo (music)|demo]] recordings produced during the games' development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vgmdb.net/album/26814 |title=POCS-21032~4 &#124; Sonic The Hedgehog 1&2 Soundtrack |work=VGMdb |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> The third disc contains \"[[Sweet Sweet Sweet]]\" by Dreams Come True,<ref name=\"musicday\" /> its English-language version \"Sweet Dream\", and 2006 remixes of both songs by singer [[Akon]], used in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (2006 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"Famitsu Japan\">{{cite web|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 1 & 2 soundtrack - Dreams Come True|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201110/12051735.html|website=Famitsu|publisher=Famitsu Japan|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Famitsu Japan\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldfarb|first1=Andrew|title=The Greatest Video Game Music 2 Tracklisting Revealed|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2012/09/14/the-greatest-video-game-music-tracklisting-revealed|website=IGN|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Person|first1=Chirs|title=90s Sonic The Hedgehog CDs Were Pretty Sexual|url=http://kotaku.com/90s-sonic-the-hedgehog-cds-were-pretty-sexual-1647712876|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=27 November 2014|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Release===\n[[Sega]] launched a $10 million advertising campaign for ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2''.<ref name=globe>{{cite news |first=Frederic M. |last=Biddle |title=Sega vs. Nintendo: The Rematch|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|page=Economy 43|date=1992-12-08}}</ref>  Sega sought a global release date to make the game available in all stores on the same day, a fairly novel concept at the time.  This required Sega to reconfigure its distribution system to ensure that games were available in all major stores.  The release date, Tuesday, November 24, 1992 was marketed as \"Sonic 2s day\".  While the Genesis release in North America and the [[Mega Drive]] release in Europe both released the game on this day, Sega made the game available a few days before in Japan on November 21, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=12085|work=Famitsu|publisher=Famitsu Japan|script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30d8\u30c3\u30b8\u30db\u30c3\u30b02 \uff08\u30de\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30b7\u30b9\u30c6\u30e0\u7248\uff09|language=Japanese|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Blake J.|title=Console Wars: Sega, Nintendo, and the Battle That Defined a Generation|year=2014|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-06-227669-8|pages=227\u2013228, 273\u2013275, 372}}</ref>  400,000 copies of ''Sonic 2'' were sold in the first seven days after release<ref name=globe/> and over 6 million in the lifespan of the console (only 180,000 of which were in Japan<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness World Records 2008 : Gamer's Edition.|date=2008|publisher=Guinness World Records|location=London|isbn=978-1-904994-20-6|page=114}}</ref>).<ref name=\"Gamasutra\"/>\n\n=== Cut content ===\n''Sonic 2'' is believed to have been planned to have [[time travel]] aspects and was originally developed alongside ''[[Sonic CD]]'' as the same game,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]|issue=1|p=90|title=Mega Mouth|date=October 1992}}</ref> but ''Sonic CD'' eventually became a separate game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/12/16/sonic-cd-review-2|title=Sonic CD Review|last=DeVries|first=Jack|date=2011-12-15|work=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref> A demonstration cartridge of ''Sonic 2'' was stolen at a [[New York City]] toy show early in 1992. The theft was attributed to a lack of security. The prototype ROM was rediscovered by fan Simon Wai on a Chinese website,<ref name=\"atlantic\" /> and features playable sections of two cut levels: Wood Zone and Hidden Palace Zone.<ref name=\"gspyarticle\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.xbox.gamespy.com/articles/654/654750p4.html | title=GameSpy: Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! | work=[[GameSpy]] | accessdate=2007-02-27}}</ref><ref name=\"kikarticle\">{{cite web | url=http://archive.videogamesdaily.com/features/sega_sonicteam_sonic_iv_nov05_p2.asp | title=Kikizo Games: Features: Sonic Team Interview November 2005 (Page 2) | work=[[Kikizo]]|publisher=Kikizo, Ltd. | accessdate=2007-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Dave|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 Android & iOS remaster restores cut Hidden Palace Zone|url=https://www.vg247.com/2013/12/12/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-android-ios-remaster-restores-cut-hidden-palace-zone/|website=VG247|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHidden Palace Zone was planned as a secret stage accessed by collecting Chaos Emeralds. According to Naka, the stage would explain where the Chaos Emeralds came from and grant Sonic his Super Sonic powers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.xbox.gamespy.com/articles/654/654750p4.html |title=GameSpy: Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! - Page 4 |work=GameSpy|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> It was removed for lack of time and cartridge space, and a different version was used in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]''. The 2013 remastered [[iOS]] port includes a redesigned Hidden Palace Zone as an optional stage.<ref name=\"joystiqremaster\" /> During development, Sega released mockup images of a cut desert-themed level,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=47|p=14|title=Sonic Mystery|author=Earth Angel|date=June 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Backstage with Sonic the Hedgehog 2|publisher=Sega|journal=Game Players Sega Guide|date=December 1992|p=16}}</ref> and the stolen 1992 prototype features an unused level slot titled \"Genocide City\".<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web|last1=Kemps|first1=Heidi|title=A Quest for the Secret Origins of Lost Video-Game Levels|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/07/a-quest-to-find-the-secret-origins-of-lost-video-game-levels/373925/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> According to Naka, the third act of Metropolis Zone was planned as a different stage, but was cut. Feeling it would be a shame to waste the finished map, the team redesigned it as an additional act for Metropolis Zone.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sonic Jam: Official Guide \u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30b8\u30e3\u30e0\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9|language=Japanese|date=1997|isbn=978-4-797-30337-7}}</ref>\n\n==Other versions and rereleases==\n\n===8-bit version===\n{{Main|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (8-bit video game)}}\nA separate version of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' was developed by [[Aspect Co.|Aspect]] and released for the 8-bit [[Master System]] and [[Sega Game Gear|Game Gear]] systems. Though based on the original game, it has different [[level design]]s and a different plot, in which Tails is kidnapped and Sonic must rescue him. <ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=IDG|title=Game Gear Preview: 2|author=The Unknown Gamer|issue=39|page=114|date=October 1992}}</ref>\n\n===2013 remaster===\nA [[Video game remake|remastered]] mobile port was released for [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[Windows Phone]] on December 12, 2013. It was developed from scratch by [[Christian Whitehead|Christian \"Taxman\" Whitehead]] and Simon \"Stealth\" Thomley of Headcannon using the [[Retro Engine]], previously used in the 2011 ''[[Sonic CD]]'' remaster. This version adds enhancements such as widescreen graphics, Knuckles as a playable character, time and boss attack modes, online multiplayer, additional multiplayer stages, Tails's flying and swimming abilities from ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'', the previously unreleased Hidden Palace Zone,<ref name=\"joystiqremaster\">{{cite web|last=Cowan |first=Danny |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/12/11/remastered-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-hits-android-ios-tomorrow-with/ |title=Remastered Sonic the Hedgehog 2 hits Android, iOS tomorrow with bonus Hidden Palace Zone |work=[[Joystiq]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=2013-12-11 |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> and a [[post-credits scene]] which depicts the Death Egg crash-landing on [[Sonic the Hedgehog 3|Angel Island]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (2013)|date=December 12, 2013|developer=Christian Whitehead|publisher=Sega|level=Post-credits scene}}</ref> Shaun Musgrave of [[TouchArcade]] declared it the \"definitive version\" of the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Musgrave|first1=Shaun|title=Sonic The Hedgehog 2 Remastered Review|url=http://toucharcade.com/2013/12/16/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-remastered-review-setting-right-what-once-went-wrong/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> The iOS version was updated in 2016, adding compatibility for [[Apple TV]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dotson|first1=Carter|title='Sonic the Hedgehog' Remaster Now on Apple TV, 'Sonic 2' and 'Sonic CD' Later This Month|url=http://toucharcade.com/2016/03/17/sonic-the-hedgehog-remaster-now-on-apple-tv-sonic-2-and-sonic-cd-later-this-month/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Compilations===\n{{see also|List of Sonic the Hedgehog compilations}}\nThe game has been rereleased on compilations including ''[[Sonic Compilation]]'' (1995) for Genesis;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-classics-3-in-1-sonic-compilation/gen-12179|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Classics 3 In 1 (Sonic Compilation)|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Jam]]'' (1997) for [[Sega Saturn]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-jam/saturn-1784|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Jam - Saturn|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Mega Collection]]'' (2002) for [[Nintendo GameCube]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/11/12/sonic-mega-collection|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Mega Collection|last=Mirabella|first=Fran|date=2002-11-02|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Mega Collection Plus]]'' (2004) for [[PlayStation 2]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], and PC;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/04/sonic-mega-collection-plus|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Mega Collection Plus|last=Goldstein|first=Hilary|date=2004-11-03|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sega Genesis Collection]]'' (2006) for PlayStation 2 and [[PlayStation Portable]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/16/sega-genesis-collection-review-2|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sega Genesis Collection Review|last=Goldstein|first=Hilary|date=2006-11-15|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection]]'' (2009) for [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/02/12/sonics-ultimate-genesis-collection-review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection|last=Miller|first=Greg|accessdate=2014-11-16|date=2009-02-12}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Classic Collection]]'' (2010) for [[Nintendo DS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/06/sonic-classic-collection-review|title=Sonic Classic Collection Review|last=Harris|first=Craig|date=2010-03-05|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===Digital ports===\nThe game was made available for download on [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] on June 11, 2007,<ref name=\"NWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/vcArt.cfm?artid=13596 |title=Virtual Console Mondays: June 11, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 |work=Nintendo World Report}}</ref> [[PlayStation 3]] via the [[PlayStation Network]] on April 19, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2011/03/02/new-playstation-plus-content-for-march-april-2011/ |title=New PlayStation Plus Content For March & April 2011|work=PlayStation Blog|publisher=Sony|date=2011-03-02|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> and [[Xbox 360]] via [[Xbox Live Arcade]], the latter having enhancements such as online leaderboards, achievements, and online play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marketplace.xbox.com/en-US/Product/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/66acd000-77fe-1000-9115-d80258410863 |title=Sonic The Hedgehog 2 - Game Detail Page |work=Xbox.com|publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref> Various mobile phone versions exist as well, including the iOS release.<ref name=\"IGNiPhoneRev\">{{cite web |url=http://wireless.ign.com/articles/108/1084753p1.html |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 iPhone Review |author=Buchanan, Levi |date=2010-04-20 |work=IGN |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=2010-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425025449/http://wireless.ign.com/articles/108/1084753p1.html |archivedate=April 25, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The game was released as part of the [[Nintendo 3DS]] ''[[3D Classics]]'' line in Japan on July 22, 2015, with a release in North America and Europe initially slated for September 2015, before being pushed back to October 8. This version of the game is enhanced using the stereoscopic 3D technology of the 3DS .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sega.com/2015/04/14/segas-3d-classics-return-this-summer-with-sega-genesis-games-for-nintendo-3ds/|title=SEGA\u2019s 3D Classics Return this Summer with SEGA Genesis Games for Nintendo 3DS|work=SEGA|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lamoreux|first1=Ben|title=3D Sonic the Hedgehog 2 is Coming to eShop|url=http://www.gamnesia.com/news/3d-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-is-coming-to-eshop|website=Gamnesia|accessdate=2016-03-13|date=2015-09-28}}</ref> In 2018, Sega announced a [[Nintendo Switch]] port would be released as part of the [[Sega Ages]] product line. It includes most of the features added to the 3DS version, and added the option to use Sonic's Drop Dash ability from ''[[Sonic Mania]]'' and a [[time attack]] mode, plus the lock-on game ''Knuckles in Sonic 2''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistar |title=Sega Ages\u2019 Sonic 2, Columns II, Out Run, Thunder Force AC Gets New Info And Screenshots |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/13/sega-ages-sonic-2-columns-ii-out-run-thunder-force-ac-gets-new-info-and-screenshots/ |website=Siliconera |accessdate=September 13, 2018 |date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| GR = (Gen) 88%<!-- Please only use two digits of precision, per [[Template:Video game reviews/doc#Guidelines]] --><ref name=gr>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/563343-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/index.html |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' for Genesis |work=[[GameRankings]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-10-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209015445/https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/563343-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/index.html |archivedate=December 9, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| MC = (X360) 82/100<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_360\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 for Xbox 360 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2014-11-27}}</ref><br>(iOS) 60/100<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_ios\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 for iPhone/iPad Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2014-11-27}}</ref><br>(3DS) 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/3d-sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=3D ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' for 3DS Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| CVG = 94%<ref>''Computer & Video Games'', issue 132 (November 1992)</ref>\n| EGM = 35/40<ref>''Electronic Gaming Monthly'', ''1998 Video Game Buyer's Guide'', page 87</ref>\n| EuroG = (X360) 9/10<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>\n| Fam = 30/40<ref>''Famitsu'', issue 206</ref>\n| GameFan = 197/200<ref>''GameFan'', volume 1, issue 2 (December 1992), pages 9 & 14-17</ref>\n| GI = 27.25/30<ref>''Game Informer'', issue 8 (January/February 1993), pages 56-57</ref><br />9.5/10<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Game Informer |title=Classic Reviews: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |date=May 2002 |p=104 |volume=12 |issue=109}}</ref>\n| GSpot = (X360) 8/10<ref name=\"GSpotX360Rev\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6178735/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Xbox 360) Review |accessdate=2007-10-21 |date=September 13, 2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><br>(WII) 7.5/10<ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/>\n| IGN = (WII) 8.5/10<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\"/><br>(X360) 7.9/10<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/>\n| ONM = (WII) 94%<ref name=\"ONMRev\">{{cite web |last=East |first=Tom |title=''Sonic The Hedgehog 2'': The blue hedgehog returns |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/2532/reviewssonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/ |work=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526140144/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/2532/reviewssonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/ |archivedate=2013-05-26 |accessdate=February 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |date=2008-01-11}}</ref>\n| OXM = (X360) 9/10<ref name=gr/>\n| TA = (iOS) {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2010/04/19/sonic-2-another-genesis-game-wrapped-in-segas-emulator/ |title='Sonic 2' \u2013 Another Genesis Game Wrapped in Sega's Emulator |last=Hodapp |first=Eli |date=April 19, 2010 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Custom reviewers -->\n| rev1 = ''[[Bad Influence!]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>''Bad Influence'', issue 2, pages 46-47</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]''\n| rev2Score = 96%<ref name=MMSegaRev/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]''\n| rev3Score = 94%<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Game Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]] |publisher=Future Publishing |date=November 1992 |issue=2 |pages=36\u201341 |url=http://www.outofprintarchive.com/catalogue/mega/MEGA2.html |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mega Zone]]''\n| rev4Score = 96%<ref>{{cite journal |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |journal=[[Mega Zone]] |date=January 1993 |issue=25 |pages=31\u201333 |url=http://info.sonicretro.org/Review_-_Sonic_the_Hedgehog_2_%28Megazone,_January_1993%29}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''Sega-16''\n| rev5Score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sega-16.com/2004/07/sonic-the-hedgehog-2/ |title=Sega-16 - ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |author=Dyson Turner |publisher=Sega-16 |date=July 17, 2004 |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Sega Force]]''\n| rev6Score = 97%<ref>{{cite journal |title=Reviewed: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Mega Drive) |journal=[[Sega Force]] |publisher=[[Impact Magazines]] |date=December 1992 |issue=12 |pages=14\u20136 |url=http://www.smspower.org/Scans/SegaForce-Magazine-Issue12?gallerypage=16 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Sega Force Mega]]''\n| rev7Score = 95%<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sonic 2 |journal=[[Sega Force Mega]] |publisher=Impact Magazines |date=August 1993 |volume=2 |issue=1 |page=91}}</ref>\n<!-- Awards -->\n| award1Pub = ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''\n| award1 = [[Game of the Year|Best Game of the Year]] (Genesis)<ref name=\"egmbuyersguide1993\"/>\n| award2Pub = [[GameFan|''GameFan'' Golden Megawards]]\n| award2 = Best Action Platform Game<ref>''GameFan'', volume 1, issue 3 (January 1993), pages 70-71</ref>\n| award3Pub = ''[[Game Informer]]''\n| award3 = Best Action/Adventure Game, <br /> Best Graphics in a Video Game<ref>''Game Informer'', issue 8 (January/February 1993), page 34</ref>\n| award4Pub = ''[[GamePro]]''\n| award4 = Action/Adventure Game of the Year, <br /> 16-Bit Game of the Year (Runner-Up), <br /> Award for Excellence in Graphics (Runner-Up)<ref>''GamePro'', issue 44 (March 1993), pages 22-24</ref>\n| award5Pub = ''[[MegaTech]]''\n| award5 = Hyper Game\n}}\n\nDue to the popularity of its predecessor, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' already had an established fanbase anticipating its release.<ref name=IGNWiiRev/><ref name=EGM100/> The game received critical acclaim, accumulating an aggregate score of 88% on [[GameRankings]] based on eight reviews.<ref name=gr/> The improvements to the gameplay in comparison to its predecessor were praised. ''[[GamePro]]'' commented that \"Sonic 2's game play mechanics are the same as Sonic 1's with a few cool exceptions.\" They gave it a 4.5 out of 5 for sound and a perfect 5.0 in every other category (graphics, control, and fun factor).<ref name=GProrev>{{cite journal |title=Pro Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |author=The Unknown Gamer |journal=GamePro |publisher=IDG |issue=42 |date=January 1993 |pages=46\u201347 |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/5/54/GamePro_US_042.pdf}}</ref> Lucas Thomas of [[IGN]] proclaimed that the game \"offered more of everything. More characters, more levels. More music, moves and baddies to beat\", and that the new spin dash move \"enhanced the speed of the gameplay, as Sonic no longer had to have a long stretch of straightaway to get up to his signature blazing velocity any more.\"<ref name=IGNWiiRev/> Ellie Gibson of ''[[Eurogamer]]'', reviewing the Xbox Live Arcade port, wrote that \"SEGA has been sensible enough to leave things alone. All the original levels are present and correct. They are as expansive and exciting as ever. The sheer speed of the game still has the power to thrill as you send Sonic zooming, spinning and bouncing in all directions.\"<ref name=EuroGRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |last=Gibson |first=Ellie |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=September 17, 2007 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Frank Provo of ''[[GameSpot]]'' wrote \"Play through it and you'll understand why it helped sell a ton of Genesis consoles back in the day. It's a fun platformer and does everything a sequel is supposed to do. It resolves many of the first game's shortcomings and incorporates a slew of minor upgrades that cumulatively amount to a fresh experience.\"<ref name=GSpotWiiRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6172587/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Wii) Review |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |date=June 15, 2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> Justin Towell of ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' called the sequel \"an improvement in every respect\", citing the \"improved Special Stage with pseudo-3D shenanigans, a greater emphasis on speed, better graphics, [and] another incredible soundtrack\" as examples.<ref name=GamesRadarRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sonics-2d-classics-re-reviewed/5/?page=5 |title=''Sonic'''s 2D classics re-reviewed |last=Towell |first=Justin |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=April 16, 2008 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Tom East of ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' called the game \"arguably the best game in the series and easily one of the best platform games ever\".<ref name=ONMRev/> The main objects of criticism were the two-player mode and the inclusion of the character Tails; reviewers disliked the image distortion brought about by the squeezed and flickering graphics,<ref name=IGNWiiRev/><ref name=GamesRadarRev/><ref name=GProrev/> and Tails was considered to be \"useless\" and \"irritating\" due to his interference in boss battles.<ref name=EuroGRev/><ref name=GamesRadarRev/> By contrast, ''GamePro'' described Tails as \"about the cutest companion that any Sonic fan could ask for\" and said the game's biggest problem is that it is too easy, to the point where even unskilled players would quickly breeze through it. However, the reviewer noted that finding each stage's secrets provides the game with challenge and longevity.<ref name=GProrev/>\n\nCritics praised the game's level design and graphics. ''GamePro'' assessed that the \"graphics are actually better than the original's. The rich variety of scenery, slightly larger sprites, and extra-added attitude help the spunky hedgehog paint video game magic.\"<ref name=GProrev/> Gibson called the variation in the game's environments \"impressive\",<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> and Andy Eddy of ''[[TeamXbox]]'' described the graphics as \"bright\" and \"colorful\".<ref name=\"TeamXboxRev\">{{cite web |url=http://reviews.teamxbox.com/xbox-360/1382/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/p1/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521073319/http://reviews.teamxbox.com/xbox-360/1382/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/p1/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review (Xbox 360) |last=Eddy |first=Andy |work=[[TeamXbox]] |date=September 18, 2007 |archivedate=May 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Despite the reduction in the number of acts per level to two from the first game's three, the levels themselves were said to be larger and more memorable.<ref name=GProrev/><ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/><ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/12/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review-2 |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=November 22, 2019 |date=September 12, 2007 |first=Craddock |last=David |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis}}</ref> Provo pointed out that \"Sega concocted new backgrounds in the same colorful style as those from the first game, then jazzed them up with animated highlights such as dancing flowers and shimmering lakes.\"<ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/> However, the later stages were considered to be difficult and complex.<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/><ref name=\"TeamXboxRev\"/> Towell also noted that \"When Sonic is hurtling around the screen, [the game] could be criticized for 'playing itself'\".<ref name=\"GamesRadarRev\"/> Opinions on the special stages were divided. Gibson described the visuals of these stages as \"dreadfully blocky\",<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> and David Craddock of IGN felt that the inclusion of Tails in the stages was \"detrimental at best, since he's always colliding with bombs, thus causing the player to lose valuable rings.\"<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/> However, those who spoke positively of the special stages approved of the visual effects.<ref name=GProrev/><ref name=MMSegaRev>{{cite magazine|title=Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |magazine=[[Mean Machines Sega]] |date=November 1992 |issue=2 |pages=60\u20133 |url=http://info.sonicretro.org/Review_-_Sonic_the_Hedgehog_2_%28Mean_Machines_Sega,_November_1992%29 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=GamesRadarRev/> ''GamePro'' elaborated, \"Theoretically, the Genesis isn't capable of scaling, but Sonic's Bonus Rounds are gonna make you wonder!\"<ref name=GProrev/>\n\nSubsequent re-releases also saw positive reviews.<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_360\"/> Thomas wrote that the Virtual Console version was \"an easy thumbs-up\".<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\"/> The Xbox Live Arcade version's low selling price and the availability of an online mode attracted Gibson's attention: \"It's also much cheaper. Just GBP 4.25 will buy you hours of fun. Not millions of hours, because games were shorter in those days.\"<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Craddock proclaimed that \"''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' holds up as not only one of the best games available on Sega's memorable 16-bit machine, but also a worthy addition to any XBLA library.\"<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/> The iOS version was met with middling reviews,<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_ios\"/> with criticism focused on the subpar quality of the port and lack of multiplayer.<ref name=\"IGNiPhoneRev\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-iphone-171311.phtml |title=Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' iPhone |last=Sterling |first=Jim |date=April 19, 2010 |website=Destructoid |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' had sold over 6 million copies,<ref name=\"Gamasutra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/130268/a_detailed_crossexamination_of_.php?page=2 |title=A Detailed Cross-Examination of Yesterday and Today's Best-Selling Platform Games |page=5 |accessdate=2019-01-28 |date=2006-08-04 |first=Daniel |last=Boutros |work=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> making it the [[List of best-selling video games#Sega Mega Drive/Genesis|second best-selling game for the Sega Genesis]] (after the original ''Sonic the Hedgehog''). The game was a bestseller in the UK charts for 2 months.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Mega |issue=6 |date=March 1993 |title=Official Gallup UK Mega Drive Sales Chart}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' named it the best Genesis game of 1992,<ref name=\"egmbuyersguide1993\">{{cite magazine |year=1993 |title=Buyer's Guide: Best Game of the Year (Genesis) |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |volume= |issue= |id= |quote=Sega's famous mascot -- Sonic the Hedgehog is back for his second visit to the Genesis, and this version is hot! With 8 megabits of memory good ol' Sonic has a lot more room to do cool tricks and this is what makes this version stand head and shoulders above all the other Genesis games that came out this year. All in all, Sonic 2 is the best Genesis cart to come along in a long time!}}</ref> and number 71 on their 1997 list of the best console video games of all time. While they said that ''Sonic CD'' (ranked at number 17) was unquestionably better, they defended the multiplayer mode, contending that \"Although it looks a little squashed, the vs. races are a lot of fun.\"<ref name=EGM100>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=114}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]'' placed the game at #36 in their \"Top Sega Mega Drive Games of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]|issue=26|page=74|publisher=[[Maverick Magazines]]|date=November 1994}}</ref> In 2000, ''[[Game Informer]]'' ranked ''Sonic 2'' number 61 on its \"Top 100 Games of All Time\" list, calling it \"the most challenging and finely polished ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' title.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |date=August 2001 |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |volume=11 |issue=100 |page=28}}</ref> In 2010, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' took first place in the results of a survey conducted by ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' to determine the fan-favorite game in the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/17169/features/your-best-sonic-games/?page=3 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009040750/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/17169/features/your-best-sonic-games/?page=3 |title=Nintendo Feature: Your Best ''Sonic'' games |last=East |first=Thomas |work=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |date=May 15, 2010 |archivedate=October 9, 2014 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> In 2011, GameZone named ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' the second-best title in the series (behind ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'').<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamezone.com/editorials/top_10_sonic_games_of_all_time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207060329/http://www.gamezone.com/editorials/top_10_sonic_games_of_all_time |title=Top 10 ''Sonic'' Games of All Time |last=Sanchez |first=David |work=GameZone |date=July 7, 2011 |archivedate=December 7, 2011 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' named ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' the best ''Sonic'' title of all time and the second-best Genesis title of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/3/ |title=The best ''Sonic'' games of all time |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 19, 2017 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-sega-genesis-games-all-time/5/ |title=Best Sega Genesis/Mega Drive games of all time |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=June 21, 2017 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Sonic 2''{{'}}s success was a major factor in Sega catching up to Nintendo in the early-1990s console wars.<ref name=consolewars>{{cite web|last1=Claiborn|first1=Samuel|title=21 Crazy Facts About Sonic And The Console War He Started|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/06/26/21-crazy-facts-about-sonic-and-the-console-war-he-started|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It brought their market share up to 40% within six months of its release.<ref name=\"GSRev\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6178735/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=2007-10-21 |year=2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> Tails, whom ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' introduced, went on to become one of the most prominent characters in the series, appearing as Sonic's sidekick in most ''Sonic'' media, including in later games such as ''[[Sonic Colors]]'', ''[[Sonic Generations]]'', and ''[[Sonic Lost World]]''. ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2''{{'}}s popularity extended to various merchandise such as comic books such as ''[[Sonic the Comic]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ogrecave.com/interviews/jameswallis.shtml |title=Interviews: James Wallis |author=Allan Sugarbaker |date=24 September 2001 |work=OgreCave.com |publisher= |accessdate=22 January 2012|quote=I teamed up with Carl Sargent and Marc Gascoigne to produce four more Sonic books, novels this time, for Virgin Publishing, under the pseudonym of 'Martin Adams'.}}</ref> a [[Sonic the Hedgehog (TV series)|television series]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/KidVid/public/report/19/report.faces?id=56800|title=FCC 398 Children's Television Programming Report|date=March 24, 2005|work=Licensing.FCC.gov|accessdate=7 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315233607/http://licensing.fcc.gov/KidVid/public/report/19/report.faces?id=56800|archivedate=March 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and a sequel, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'', which received similar acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 3|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586472-sonic-the-hedgehog-3/index.html|publisher=GameRankings|accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor Sonic's 20th anniversary, Sega released ''Sonic Generations'', which [[Video game remake|remade]] aspects of various past games from the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic Generations overview|url=http://uk.ign.com/games/sonic-generations/pc-119890|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> The PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, and PC versions contained a remade \"Chemical Plant\" level.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kollar|first1=Phil|title=See Sonic's Classic Chemical Plant Zone From Two Perspectives|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/ps3/archive/2011/08/08/see-sonic-39-s-classic-chemical-plant-zone-from-two-perspectives.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=GameStop|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It also contained a remake of the final boss fight, the Death Egg Robot, as the Classic Era boss of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=NYCC 11: Death Egg Robot Boss|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/6lfx0a/sonic-generations-nycc-11--death-egg-robot-boss-walkthrough|website=[[GameTrailers]]|publisher=DFY Media|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> Separately, the [[Nintendo 3DS]] version of the game contained a remake of the \"Casino Night\" level.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic Generations Shots Show Casino Night Action|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2011/09/sonic_generations_shots_show_casino_night_action|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> A \"Casino Night\" themed [[pinball]] minigame was made available for download as a pre-order bonus for the console versions at [[GameStop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=Sonic's Casino Night Pinball Comes to PC on Dec. 26|url=http://kotaku.com/5866163/sonics-casino-night-pinball-comes-to-pc-on-dec-26/|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> Remade versions of Chemical Plant and Oil Ocean also appear in the 2017 game ''[[Sonic Mania]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Kat|title=Sonic Mania Brings Back the Best Sonic Level Ever|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/sonic-mania-brings-back-the-best-sonic-level-ever|website=USgamer|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD}}In 2008, an unofficial, high-definition remake was announced titled ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD'', which included development members who would later work on ''Sonic Mania''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://kotaku.com/5050852/sonic-2-hd-tech-demo-released-requires-serious-blast-processing | title=Sonic 2 HD tech demo released, requires serious blast processing | publisher=Kotaku | date=16 September 2008 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=McWhertor, Micheal}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PagodaWestGames |number=759174613146345472 |date=July 29, 2016 |title=Jared and Tom, formerly a part of S2HD are in charge of level design/art and @teelopesmusic is doing the music.}}</ref> In 2012, it was reported that a potential [[keylogger]] was included with an alpha build of the game, which led to the project being discontinued due to the controversy.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://kotaku.com/5900549/sonic-2-hd-contains-keylogger-delete-immediately | title=Sonic 2 HD contains keylogger, delete immediately | publisher=Kotaku | date=10 April 2012 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Plunkett, Luke}}</ref> In 2014, the project was restarted under a new development team.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/06/29/fan-crafted-sonic-2-hd-project-pokes-its-nose-out-once-more/ | title=Fan-crafted Sonic 2 HD project pokes its nose out once more | publisher=[[Engadget]] | date=6 June 2017 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Prell, S}}</ref> The final version is planned to feature additional stages and the option to play levels as [[Knuckles the Echidna]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/24/5837612/the-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-hd-fan-project-is-back-from-the-dead | title=The Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD fan project is back from the dead (correction) | website=Polygon | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Ray Corriea, Alexa}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vc.sega.jp/vc_sonic2/ Official Sega webpage] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/Ep8oLkJXWlgKpLFfuEve8Gb_qEWumasV Official Nintendo webpage]\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n{{Sonic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Video games|Japan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonic The Hedgehog 2 (16-Bit)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega Technical Institute games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Sonic Team games]]\n[[Category:Sonic the Hedgehog video games]]\n[[Category:Tiger handheld games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games with expansion packs]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Sega Mega Drive/Genesis game|the Master System and Game Gear game|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (8-bit video game)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sonic the Hedgehog 2\n| image = File:Sonic_2_US_Cover.jpg\n| caption = US cover art\n| developer = [[Sega Technical Institute]]\n| publisher = [[Sega]]\n| director = Masaharu Yoshii\n| producer = [[Shinobu Toyoda]]\n| designer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Hirokazu Yasuhara]]|Takahiro Anto|Yutaka Sugano}}\n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|[[Yasushi Yamaguchi]]|Jina Ishiwatari|[[Rieko Kodama]]|Tim Skelly}}\n| programmer = {{Unbulleted list|[[Yuji Naka]]|Bill Willis|Masanobu Yamamoto}}\n| composer = [[Masato Nakamura]]\n| series = ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n| released = {{collapsible list|title={{nobold|November 21, 1992}}|\n'''Sega Genesis'''{{Video game release|JP|November 21, 1992|[[North America|NA]]/[[Europe|EU]]|November 24, 1992|AUS|December 1, 1992}}'''iOS''', '''Android'''{{Video game release|WW|December 12, 2013}}'''Windows Phone'''{{Video game release|WW|December 14, 2013}}'''Nintendo 3DS'''{{Video game release|JP|July 22, 2015|WW|October 8, 2015}}'''Nintendo Switch'''{{Video game release|WW|February 13, 2020}}\n}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Sega Genesis]]|[[Nintendo 3DS]]|[[iOS]]|[[Windows Phone]]|[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Apple TV]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'''''|\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30d8\u30c3\u30b8\u30db\u30c3\u30b0{{ruby|2|\u30c4\u30fc}}|Sonikku za Hejjihoggu Ts\u016b|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[platform game]] developed and published by [[Sega]] for the [[Sega Genesis]] console, released worldwide in November 1992. It is the second main entry in the ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, and introduced [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic]]'s sidekick, [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower]], controllable by a second player. In the story, Sonic and Tails must stop series antagonist [[Dr. Ivo Robotnik]] from stealing the [[Chaos Emeralds]] to power his [[space station]], the Death Egg.\n\nDevelopment of the game began in November 1991. The game was developed by both Japanese and American staff at [[Sega Technical Institute]]. The game was directed by Masaharu Yoshii and produced by [[Shinobu Toyoda]], with game design led by [[Hirokazu Yasuhara]] and music composed by [[Masato Nakamura]]. Art director Tim Skelly designed the appearance of the new 3D special stages based on a [[tech demo]] created by [[Yuji Naka]]. The staff increased the speed of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' in comparison to its predecessor.\n\n''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' sold over six million copies, making it the second-bestselling Genesis game behind the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''. Cited as one of the [[greatest video games of all time]], it received acclaim for its level design, visuals and music, although its multiplayer mode was criticized. It has been rereleased on various platforms; a remastered version developed using the [[Retro Engine]] released on [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] in December 2013. Two direct sequels, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' and ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'', were released in 1994.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Aquatic Ruins from Sonic 2 for Mega Drive.png|thumb|left|Sonic and Tails hopping across pillars in the third stage, Aquatic Ruin Zone]]\n''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' is a [[2D computer graphics|2D]] [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform game]].<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2007/06/11/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=January 28, 2019 |date=June 11, 2007 |first=Thomas |last=Lucas M. |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis}}</ref> The game stars [[Sonic the Hedgehog (character)|Sonic the Hedgehog]] and his sidekick, [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower]], who is described as having idolized Sonic as a child and wanting to keep up with him.<ref name=\"m3\">''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 3.</ref> At the game's start, the player can select to either play as Sonic, Tails, or both. The difference between the two is purely cosmetic; the two both have identical abilities.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 8.</ref> In the dual mode, players control Sonic while Tails runs along beside him. A second player can join in at any time and control Tails separately.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 7.</ref> The game takes place over a series of levels, each divided into one, two, or three acts with a [[boss (video gaming)|boss]] fight with Robotnik at the end of the last act. Certain levels have features that are unique to them; for example, Emerald Hill has corkscrew-like loops, and Chemical Plant has boost pads that instantly put Sonic at his top speed.<ref name=\"m3\"/> The character can jump on enemies to defeat them; the game also introduces a new move, the \"spin dash\" or \"Super Dash Attack\", by which the player curls in a ball and spins while stationary, resulting in a speed boost.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 6.</ref> When the player is attacked by an enemy without rings, is crushed, falls off-screen, drowns, or exceeds the act's ten-minute limit, they lose a [[health (gaming)|life]] and return to the start of the act or from the most recently passed [[checkpoint (video gaming)|checkpoint]].<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 9.</ref> Dying with zero lives gives the player a [[game over]].<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 18.</ref>\n\n[[File:Sonic 2 SpecialStage.gif|thumb|right|The game's special stages, in which the player collects rings in hopes of obtaining a Chaos Emerald, are presented in 3D, unlike the rest of the game.]]\n\nWhen the player collects at least 50 rings and passes a checkpoint, they can warp to a \"special stage\".<ref name=stages>{{cite web|last1=Nelson|first1=Jared|title=A Guide to 'Sonic The Hedgehog' Version 2.0's Hidden Level-select, Debug Mode, and Many More Secrets|url=http://toucharcade.com/2013/05/27/a-guide-to-sonic-the-hedgehog-version-2-0s-hidden-level-select-debug-mode-and-many-more-secrets/|website=TouchArcade|publisher=[[Arnold Kim]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> In these stages, the player runs through a pseudo-[[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[half-pipe]] course, collecting rings and dodging bombs. A set amount of rings must be collected to pass through each of three checkpoints and in turn to obtain the emerald itself. If Sonic collides with a bomb, he loses ten rings and is immobilized momentarily. The stages rise in difficulty, and the player cannot enter any stage without passing the previous one. After finishing, the player is transported back to the star post they used to enter the special stage, with their ring-count reset to zero.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 17.</ref> When all Emeralds have been collected, Sonic can transform into Super Sonic by collecting 50 rings and jumping.<ref name=gameplay>{{cite web|last1=Creegan|first1=Dermot|title=Casual Monday: Sonic the Hedgehog 2|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2014/10/27/casual-monday-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/114175/|website=Hardcore Gamer|publisher=Disqus|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref name=stages/> Super Sonic is invincible to attacks, runs faster, and jumps further; however, he loses one ring per second and reverts to regular Sonic when his rings are depleted.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\nThe game also has a competitive mode, where two players compete against each other to the finish line, as either Sonic or Tails, in a split-screen race through three of the regular levels and a special stage. After one player finishes one of the regular levels, the other player must finish the zone within 60 seconds, or the level ends instantly. In the regular levels, players are ranked in five areas (score, time, rings held at the end of the level, total rings collected, and the number of item boxes broken). The player with wins in the most number of categories wins the level. In the Special Stage, players compete to obtain the most rings. The mode ends when all stages have been completed, or if a player loses all their lives, in which their opponent will automatically win.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, pp. 19\u201320.</ref>\n\n===''Knuckles the Echidna in Sonic the Hedgehog 2''===\n{{See also|Sonic &amp; Knuckles}}\n''Sonic & Knuckles'' was released in 1994, two years after ''Sonic 2''. The ''Sonic & Knuckles'' [[ROM cartridge|game cartridge]] features a special \"lock-on\" port into which the player can insert other Genesis cartridges. Attaching ''Sonic 2'' unlocks ''Knuckles the Echidna in Sonic the Hedgehog 2'', a variation of ''Sonic 2'' whereby the player plays as [[Knuckles the Echidna]], a character introduced in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' and not playable until ''Sonic & Knuckles''.<ref name=lockon>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic & Knuckles \"lock-on\" review|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2010/02/sonic_and_knuckles_virtual_console|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-14}}</ref> Though the game is largely identical to ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'', Knuckles is able to glide and climb walls, allowing him access to areas previously inaccessible to Sonic or Tails. However, he cannot jump as high, making some parts of the game, such as certain boss fights, more difficult. In addition, Knuckles restarts with the amount of rings he collected at checkpoints (if he loses a life), the options are unavailable, the special stages have slightly fewer rings required to collect than before (for example, ten rings fewer than in the special stages with Sonic and Tails), and the two-player mode is removed.<ref name=lockon/>\n\n==Plot==\nThe game's premise is similar to that of the original ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (1991 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]''. Sonic's nemesis, [[Dr. Ivo Robotnik]], is planning world domination through the power of the [[Chaos Emeralds]] and an army of robots powered by trapped animals. Specific to this game, he is additionally constructing an armored space station known as the Death Egg (an homage to the [[Death Star]]), also for the means of world domination.<ref>''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Genesis) instruction manual, p. 4.</ref>\n\nThe events of the game see Sonic and Tails chasing Robotnik through West Side Island, and eventually up to the Death Egg, pursuing him with Tails' biplane, the Tornado. The plane is damaged after being shot at, but Sonic still manages to infiltrate the Death Egg, alone. Once there, he battles a robotic imposter before taking on Robotnik, who is piloting a giant [[mech]]. Sonic manages to defeat the robot and it explodes, damaging the Death Egg and knocking it out of orbit. Sonic falls to the ground and is saved by Tails in the Tornado. If the player has collected all of the Chaos Emeralds, Sonic, in his [[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)#Super transformation|Super Sonic]] form, flies alongside it.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\n==Development==\nFollowing the release of the original ''Sonic the Hedgehog'', creator [[Yuji Naka]] quit [[Sega]] due to disagreements over corporate policy.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\">{{cite web|last=Horowitz|first=Ken|url=http://www.sega-16.com/2007/06/developers-den-sega-technical-institute/|title=Developer's Den: Sega Technical Institute|work=Sega-16|date=2007-06-11|accessdate=2014-07-11}}</ref><ref name=\"1up.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-sonic|title=The Essential 50 Part 28 - Sonic the Hedgehog|work=[[1UP.com]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523204203/http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-sonic|archivedate=May 23, 2011|accessdate=2014-07-21|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Mark Cerny]], who had recently founded [[Sega Technical Institute]] (STI) in California, met with Naka in Japan and offered him a higher salary and more creative freedom if he joined STI.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"1up.com\"/> Naka agreed, and [[Hirokazu Yasuhara]], the lead level designer of ''Sonic the Hedgehog'', also decided to move to STI.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"1up.com\"/> Yasuhara had been assigned to help Cerny establish STI in 1990, but the outbreak of the [[Gulf War]] delayed his move to the United States by three months, during which he joined [[Sonic Team]] and became part of the original ''Sonic'' project.<ref name=\"Yasuhara\">{{cite magazine|title=Sonic's Architect: GI Interviews Hirokazu Yasuhara|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|issue=124|volume=13|date=August 2003|pages=114\u2013116}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Thomason|first=Steve|title=Birth of a Hedgehog|magazine=[[Nintendo Power]]|issue=211|volume=20|date=January 2007|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|page=72}}</ref>\n\nDevelopment of ''Sonic 2'' began in November 1991, two months later than Cerny had intended, as Sega of America initially felt it was too soon for a sequel.<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\" /> STI handled development;<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\"/><ref name=\"gibehind\">{{cite web|last1=Shea|first1=Brian|title=The Behind-The-Scenes Story Of How Sonic 2 Became Sega\u2019s Ace In The Hole|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/21/the-behind-the-scenes-story-of-how-sonic-2-became-sega-ace-in-the-hole.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|accessdate=15 March 2018|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wrong\">{{cite web|last1=Shea|first1=Brian|title=Where Sonic Went Wrong|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/11/09/where-sonic-went-wrong.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=[[GameStop]]|accessdate=15 March 2018|date=November 14, 2006}}</ref> both American and Japanese staff contributed, although, according to team member Tim Skelly, \"Everyone attached to ''Sonic 2'' ultimately worked for Yuji Naka. I think Naka would have been much happier if he was working with an all-Japanese team, but just because of the language barrier and some cultural differences.\"<ref name=\"Sega-16 STI\" />\n\nSkelly designed the appearance of the pseudo-3D special stages, based on a [[tech demo]] created by Naka.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2SQJ8XeArso|title=G4 Icons Episode #37: Yuji Naka|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2013-04-05|accessdate=2018-03-15}} Event occurs at 8:50.</ref> The special stages were created out of [[Pre-rendering|pre-rendered]] [[3D computer graphics|3D polygons]], video of which was compressed and halved vertically and horizontally to fit in the [[ROM cartridge|game cartridge]].<ref>[http://blogs.sega.com/2015/10/ 3D Sonic The Hedgehog 2 Included in the SEGA 3D Classics], [[Sega]] (October 6, 2015)</ref> ''Sonic 2'' also introduced Sonic's sidekick [[Tails (character)|Tails]], a flying two-tailed fox, inspired by Japanese folklore about the [[kitsune]] and created by level artist [[Yasushi Yamaguchi]]. Sega of America objected to the character's name, Miles Prower (a [[pun]] on \"[[miles per hour]]\"), so he was given the nickname Tails as a compromise.<ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Blake J.|title=Console Wars: Sega, Nintendo, and the Battle That Defined a Generation|year=2014|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-06-227669-8|pages=244\u2013247}}</ref> Masaharu Yoshii served as director. The staff increased the speed of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' compared to the first game.<ref name=\"Sega illustrations\">{{cite book|title=Sega Video Game Illustrations|year=1994|work=Nippon Shuppan Hanbai (Deutschland) GmbH|location= |isbn=3-910052-50-9|page=50}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nLike the previous game, the music was composed by [[Masato Nakamura]], bassist and songwriter of the [[J-pop]] band [[Dreams Come True (band)|Dreams Come True]]. Nakamura began composing early in development with only concept images for reference, taking a similar approach to his method for ''Sonic 1''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=When I started writing the music, \"Sonic the Hedgehog 1\" was just still images...\"Sonic the Hedgehog 2\" started off the kind of the same. Just graphics.}}</ref> Nakamura treated ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' as a film and designed the music around the atmosphere that he felt from the images of the stages.<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=I wanted to treat 'Sonic the Hedgehog' as a film, my inspiration came from each screenshot, or each stage.}}</ref> Except for the graphics and some discussion with Sonic Team, Nakamura was given freedom, which he believes was the reason why he was able to create \"such melodic tunes and unusual rhythm patterns\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Nakamura|first=Masato|title=Interview with Masato Nakamura|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=There were some briefs and meetings...otherwise, they let me do as I pleased, and gave me the freedom to create music.}}</ref> Nakamura created the music while he was recording with Dreams Come True in London, working on their fifth album ''[[The Swinging Star]]''. As a gift to Sonic Team, Masato produced an alternate version of the ending theme with Dreams Come True, included on ''The Swinging Star''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Naka|first=Yuji|title=Interview with Yuju Naka|publisher=DCT Records|year=2011|type=Album Booklet|quote=Nakamura reoworked the ending theme...info a song entitled \"Sweet Sweet Sweet\" for inclusion on the Dreams Come True album}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the stage music from Chemical Plant and Casino Night Zone were remixed by [[Sega]] for use in ''[[Sonic Generations]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic Colours Soundtrack Racing to iTunes|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2011/01/sonic_colours_soundtrack_racing_to_itunes|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-14}}</ref> That October, a three-disc compilation of the music from ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' and ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' was released in Japan.<ref name=\"musicday\">{{cite web|last1=Elston|first1=Brett|title=Game music of the day: Sonic the Hedgehog 2|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/game-music-of-the-day-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/|website=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=Future US|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It compilation includes comments by Naka and an interview with Nakamura.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gantayat|first1=Anoop|title=TGS 2005: Eyes-On Sonic Next-Gen|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2005/09/17/tgs-2005-eyes-on-sonic-next-gen|website=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=A Look Back at 20 Years of Music History with Sonic|url=http://kotaku.com/5861124/sonic-music-video|website=Kotaku|publisher=Gawker Media|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> The first disc contains original tracks from both games, and the second contains Nakamura's [[Demo (music)|demo]] recordings produced during the games' development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vgmdb.net/album/26814 |title=POCS-21032~4 &#124; Sonic The Hedgehog 1&2 Soundtrack |work=VGMdb |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> The third disc contains \"[[Sweet Sweet Sweet]]\" by Dreams Come True,<ref name=\"musicday\" /> its English-language version \"Sweet Dream\", and 2006 remixes of both songs by singer [[Akon]], used in ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (2006 video game)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"Famitsu Japan\">{{cite web|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 1 & 2 soundtrack - Dreams Come True|url=http://www.famitsu.com/news/201110/12051735.html|website=Famitsu|publisher=Famitsu Japan|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Famitsu Japan\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldfarb|first1=Andrew|title=The Greatest Video Game Music 2 Tracklisting Revealed|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2012/09/14/the-greatest-video-game-music-tracklisting-revealed|website=IGN|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Person|first1=Chirs|title=90s Sonic The Hedgehog CDs Were Pretty Sexual|url=http://kotaku.com/90s-sonic-the-hedgehog-cds-were-pretty-sexual-1647712876|publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=27 November 2014|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Release===\n[[Sega]] launched a $10 million advertising campaign for ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2''.<ref name=globe>{{cite news |first=Frederic M. |last=Biddle |title=Sega vs. Nintendo: The Rematch|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|page=Economy 43|date=1992-12-08}}</ref>  Sega sought a global release date to make the game available in all stores on the same day, a fairly novel concept at the time.  This required Sega to reconfigure its distribution system to ensure that games were available in all major stores.  The release date, Tuesday, November 24, 1992 was marketed as \"Sonic 2s day\".  While the Genesis release in North America and the [[Mega Drive]] release in Europe both released the game on this day, Sega made the game available a few days before in Japan on November 21, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=12085|work=Famitsu|publisher=Famitsu Japan|script-title=ja:\u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30d8\u30c3\u30b8\u30db\u30c3\u30b02 \uff08\u30de\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30b7\u30b9\u30c6\u30e0\u7248\uff09|language=Japanese|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Blake J.|title=Console Wars: Sega, Nintendo, and the Battle That Defined a Generation|year=2014|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-06-227669-8|pages=227\u2013228, 273\u2013275, 372}}</ref>  400,000 copies of ''Sonic 2'' were sold in the first seven days after release<ref name=globe/> and over 6 million in the lifespan of the console (only 180,000 of which were in Japan<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness World Records 2008 : Gamer's Edition.|date=2008|publisher=Guinness World Records|location=London|isbn=978-1-904994-20-6|page=114}}</ref>).<ref name=\"Gamasutra\"/>\n\n=== Cut content ===\n''Sonic 2'' is believed to have been planned to have [[time travel]] aspects and was originally developed alongside ''[[Sonic CD]]'' as the same game,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]|issue=1|p=90|title=Mega Mouth|date=October 1992}}</ref> but ''Sonic CD'' eventually became a separate game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/12/16/sonic-cd-review-2|title=Sonic CD Review|last=DeVries|first=Jack|date=2011-12-15|work=IGN|publisher=Ziff Davis|accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref> A demonstration cartridge of ''Sonic 2'' was stolen at a [[New York City]] toy show early in 1992. The theft was attributed to a lack of security. The prototype ROM was rediscovered by fan Simon Wai on a Chinese website,<ref name=\"atlantic\" /> and features playable sections of two cut levels: Wood Zone and Hidden Palace Zone.<ref name=\"gspyarticle\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.xbox.gamespy.com/articles/654/654750p4.html | title=GameSpy: Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! | work=[[GameSpy]] | accessdate=2007-02-27}}</ref><ref name=\"kikarticle\">{{cite web | url=http://archive.videogamesdaily.com/features/sega_sonicteam_sonic_iv_nov05_p2.asp | title=Kikizo Games: Features: Sonic Team Interview November 2005 (Page 2) | work=[[Kikizo]]|publisher=Kikizo, Ltd. | accessdate=2007-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=Dave|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 Android & iOS remaster restores cut Hidden Palace Zone|url=https://www.vg247.com/2013/12/12/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-android-ios-remaster-restores-cut-hidden-palace-zone/|website=VG247|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHidden Palace Zone was planned as a secret stage accessed by collecting Chaos Emeralds. According to Naka, the stage would explain where the Chaos Emeralds came from and grant Sonic his Super Sonic powers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.xbox.gamespy.com/articles/654/654750p4.html |title=GameSpy: Sega's Yuji Naka Talks! - Page 4 |work=GameSpy|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> It was removed for lack of time and cartridge space, and a different version was used in ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]''. The 2013 remastered [[iOS]] port includes a redesigned Hidden Palace Zone as an optional stage.<ref name=\"joystiqremaster\" /> During development, Sega released mockup images of a cut desert-themed level,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=47|p=14|title=Sonic Mystery|author=Earth Angel|date=June 1993}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Backstage with Sonic the Hedgehog 2|publisher=Sega|journal=Game Players Sega Guide|date=December 1992|p=16}}</ref> and the stolen 1992 prototype features an unused level slot titled \"Genocide City\".<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web|last1=Kemps|first1=Heidi|title=A Quest for the Secret Origins of Lost Video-Game Levels|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/07/a-quest-to-find-the-secret-origins-of-lost-video-game-levels/373925/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> According to Naka, the third act of Metropolis Zone was planned as a different stage, but was cut. Feeling it would be a shame to waste the finished map, the team redesigned it as an additional act for Metropolis Zone.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sonic Jam: Official Guide \u30bd\u30cb\u30c3\u30af\u30b8\u30e3\u30e0\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9|language=Japanese|date=1997|isbn=978-4-797-30337-7}}</ref>\n\n==Other versions and rereleases==\n\n===8-bit version===\n{{Main|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (8-bit video game)}}\nA separate version of ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' was developed by [[Aspect Co.|Aspect]] and released for the 8-bit [[Master System]] and [[Sega Game Gear|Game Gear]] systems. Though based on the original game, it has different [[level design]]s and a different plot, in which Tails is kidnapped and Sonic must rescue him. <ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=IDG|title=Game Gear Preview: 2|author=The Unknown Gamer|issue=39|page=114|date=October 1992}}</ref>\n\n===2013 remaster===\nA [[Video game remake|remastered]] mobile port was released for [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[Windows Phone]] on December 12, 2013. It was developed from scratch by [[Christian Whitehead|Christian \"Taxman\" Whitehead]] and Simon \"Stealth\" Thomley of Headcannon using the [[Retro Engine]], previously used in the 2011 ''[[Sonic CD]]'' remaster. This version adds enhancements such as widescreen graphics, Knuckles as a playable character, time and boss attack modes, online multiplayer, additional multiplayer stages, Tails's flying and swimming abilities from ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'', the previously unreleased Hidden Palace Zone,<ref name=\"joystiqremaster\">{{cite web|last=Cowan |first=Danny |url=http://www.joystiq.com/2013/12/11/remastered-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-hits-android-ios-tomorrow-with/ |title=Remastered Sonic the Hedgehog 2 hits Android, iOS tomorrow with bonus Hidden Palace Zone |work=[[Joystiq]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=2013-12-11 |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> and a [[post-credits scene]] which depicts the Death Egg crash-landing on [[Sonic the Hedgehog 3|Angel Island]].<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 (2013)|date=December 12, 2013|developer=Christian Whitehead|publisher=Sega|level=Post-credits scene}}</ref> Shaun Musgrave of [[TouchArcade]] declared it the \"definitive version\" of the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Musgrave|first1=Shaun|title=Sonic The Hedgehog 2 Remastered Review|url=http://toucharcade.com/2013/12/16/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-remastered-review-setting-right-what-once-went-wrong/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> The iOS version was updated in 2016, adding compatibility for [[Apple TV]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dotson|first1=Carter|title='Sonic the Hedgehog' Remaster Now on Apple TV, 'Sonic 2' and 'Sonic CD' Later This Month|url=http://toucharcade.com/2016/03/17/sonic-the-hedgehog-remaster-now-on-apple-tv-sonic-2-and-sonic-cd-later-this-month/|website=TouchArcade|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Compilations===\n{{see also|List of Sonic the Hedgehog compilations}}\nThe game has been rereleased on compilations including ''[[Sonic Compilation]]'' (1995) for Genesis;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-classics-3-in-1-sonic-compilation/gen-12179|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Classics 3 In 1 (Sonic Compilation)|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Jam]]'' (1997) for [[Sega Saturn]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/sonic-jam/saturn-1784|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Jam - Saturn|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Mega Collection]]'' (2002) for [[Nintendo GameCube]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/11/12/sonic-mega-collection|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Mega Collection|last=Mirabella|first=Fran|date=2002-11-02|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic Mega Collection Plus]]'' (2004) for [[PlayStation 2]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], and PC;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/04/sonic-mega-collection-plus|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic Mega Collection Plus|last=Goldstein|first=Hilary|date=2004-11-03|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sega Genesis Collection]]'' (2006) for PlayStation 2 and [[PlayStation Portable]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/11/16/sega-genesis-collection-review-2|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sega Genesis Collection Review|last=Goldstein|first=Hilary|date=2006-11-15|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> ''[[Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection]]'' (2009) for [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/02/12/sonics-ultimate-genesis-collection-review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|title=Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection|last=Miller|first=Greg|accessdate=2014-11-16|date=2009-02-12}}</ref> and ''[[Sonic Classic Collection]]'' (2010) for [[Nintendo DS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/06/sonic-classic-collection-review|title=Sonic Classic Collection Review|last=Harris|first=Craig|date=2010-03-05|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===Digital ports===\nThe game was made available for download on [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] on June 11, 2007,<ref name=\"NWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/vcArt.cfm?artid=13596 |title=Virtual Console Mondays: June 11, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 |work=Nintendo World Report}}</ref> [[PlayStation 3]] via the [[PlayStation Network]] on April 19, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.eu.playstation.com/2011/03/02/new-playstation-plus-content-for-march-april-2011/ |title=New PlayStation Plus Content For March & April 2011|work=PlayStation Blog|publisher=Sony|date=2011-03-02|accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref> and [[Xbox 360]] via [[Xbox Live Arcade]], the latter having enhancements such as online leaderboards, achievements, and online play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marketplace.xbox.com/en-US/Product/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/66acd000-77fe-1000-9115-d80258410863 |title=Sonic The Hedgehog 2 - Game Detail Page |work=Xbox.com|publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=2012-02-18}}</ref> Various mobile phone versions exist as well, including the iOS release.<ref name=\"IGNiPhoneRev\">{{cite web |url=http://wireless.ign.com/articles/108/1084753p1.html |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 iPhone Review |author=Buchanan, Levi |date=2010-04-20 |work=IGN |publisher=Ziff Davis |accessdate=2010-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425025449/http://wireless.ign.com/articles/108/1084753p1.html |archivedate=April 25, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The game was released as part of the [[Nintendo 3DS]] ''[[3D Classics]]'' line in Japan on July 22, 2015, with a release in North America and Europe initially slated for September 2015, before being pushed back to October 8. This version of the game is enhanced using the stereoscopic 3D technology of the 3DS .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sega.com/2015/04/14/segas-3d-classics-return-this-summer-with-sega-genesis-games-for-nintendo-3ds/|title=SEGA\u2019s 3D Classics Return this Summer with SEGA Genesis Games for Nintendo 3DS|work=SEGA|accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lamoreux|first1=Ben|title=3D Sonic the Hedgehog 2 is Coming to eShop|url=http://www.gamnesia.com/news/3d-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-is-coming-to-eshop|website=Gamnesia|accessdate=2016-03-13|date=2015-09-28}}</ref> In 2018, Sega announced a [[Nintendo Switch]] port would be released as part of the [[Sega Ages]] product line. It includes most of the features added to the 3DS version, and added the option to use Sonic's Drop Dash ability from ''[[Sonic Mania]]'' and a [[time attack]] mode, plus the lock-on game ''Knuckles in Sonic 2''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Alistar |title=Sega Ages\u2019 Sonic 2, Columns II, Out Run, Thunder Force AC Gets New Info And Screenshots |url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/13/sega-ages-sonic-2-columns-ii-out-run-thunder-force-ac-gets-new-info-and-screenshots/ |website=Siliconera |accessdate=September 13, 2018 |date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| GR = (Gen) 88%<!-- Please only use two digits of precision, per [[Template:Video game reviews/doc#Guidelines]] --><ref name=gr>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/563343-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/index.html |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' for Genesis |work=[[GameRankings]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-10-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209015445/https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/563343-sonic-the-hedgehog-2/index.html |archivedate=December 9, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| MC = (X360) 82/100<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_360\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 for Xbox 360 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2014-11-27}}</ref><br>(iOS) 60/100<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_ios\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=Sonic the Hedgehog 2 for iPhone/iPad Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2014-11-27}}</ref><br>(3DS) 87/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/3d-sonic-the-hedgehog-2 |title=3D ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' for 3DS Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| CVG = 94%<ref>''Computer & Video Games'', issue 132 (November 1992)</ref>\n| EGM = 35/40<ref>''Electronic Gaming Monthly'', ''1998 Video Game Buyer's Guide'', page 87</ref>\n| EuroG = (X360) 9/10<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/>\n| Fam = 30/40<ref>''Famitsu'', issue 206</ref>\n| GameFan = 197/200<ref>''GameFan'', volume 1, issue 2 (December 1992), pages 9 & 14-17</ref>\n| GI = 27.25/30<ref>''Game Informer'', issue 8 (January/February 1993), pages 56-57</ref><br />9.5/10<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Game Informer |title=Classic Reviews: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |date=May 2002 |p=104 |volume=12 |issue=109}}</ref>\n| GSpot = (X360) 8/10<ref name=\"GSpotX360Rev\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6178735/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Xbox 360) Review |accessdate=2007-10-21 |date=September 13, 2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><br>(WII) 7.5/10<ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/>\n| IGN = (WII) 8.5/10<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\"/><br>(X360) 7.9/10<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/>\n| ONM = (WII) 94%<ref name=\"ONMRev\">{{cite web |last=East |first=Tom |title=''Sonic The Hedgehog 2'': The blue hedgehog returns |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/2532/reviewssonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/ |work=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526140144/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/2532/reviewssonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/ |archivedate=2013-05-26 |accessdate=February 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |date=2008-01-11}}</ref>\n| OXM = (X360) 9/10<ref name=gr/>\n| TA = (iOS) {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2010/04/19/sonic-2-another-genesis-game-wrapped-in-segas-emulator/ |title='Sonic 2' \u2013 Another Genesis Game Wrapped in Sega's Emulator |last=Hodapp |first=Eli |date=April 19, 2010 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Custom reviewers -->\n| rev1 = ''[[Bad Influence!]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>''Bad Influence'', issue 2, pages 46-47</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]''\n| rev2Score = 96%<ref name=MMSegaRev/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]''\n| rev3Score = 94%<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Game Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]] |publisher=Future Publishing |date=November 1992 |issue=2 |pages=36\u201341 |url=http://www.outofprintarchive.com/catalogue/mega/MEGA2.html |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mega Zone]]''\n| rev4Score = 96%<ref>{{cite journal |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |journal=[[Mega Zone]] |date=January 1993 |issue=25 |pages=31\u201333 |url=http://info.sonicretro.org/Review_-_Sonic_the_Hedgehog_2_%28Megazone,_January_1993%29}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''Sega-16''\n| rev5Score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sega-16.com/2004/07/sonic-the-hedgehog-2/ |title=Sega-16 - ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |author=Dyson Turner |publisher=Sega-16 |date=July 17, 2004 |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Sega Force]]''\n| rev6Score = 97%<ref>{{cite journal |title=Reviewed: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Mega Drive) |journal=[[Sega Force]] |publisher=[[Impact Magazines]] |date=December 1992 |issue=12 |pages=14\u20136 |url=http://www.smspower.org/Scans/SegaForce-Magazine-Issue12?gallerypage=16 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Sega Force Mega]]''\n| rev7Score = 95%<ref>{{cite journal |title=Sonic 2 |journal=[[Sega Force Mega]] |publisher=Impact Magazines |date=August 1993 |volume=2 |issue=1 |page=91}}</ref>\n<!-- Awards -->\n| award1Pub = ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''\n| award1 = [[Game of the Year|Best Game of the Year]] (Genesis)<ref name=\"egmbuyersguide1993\"/>\n| award2Pub = [[GameFan|''GameFan'' Golden Megawards]]\n| award2 = Best Action Platform Game<ref>''GameFan'', volume 1, issue 3 (January 1993), pages 70-71</ref>\n| award3Pub = ''[[Game Informer]]''\n| award3 = Best Action/Adventure Game, <br /> Best Graphics in a Video Game<ref>''Game Informer'', issue 8 (January/February 1993), page 34</ref>\n| award4Pub = ''[[GamePro]]''\n| award4 = Action/Adventure Game of the Year, <br /> 16-Bit Game of the Year (Runner-Up), <br /> Award for Excellence in Graphics (Runner-Up)<ref>''GamePro'', issue 44 (March 1993), pages 22-24</ref>\n| award5Pub = ''[[MegaTech]]''\n| award5 = Hyper Game\n}}\n\nDue to the popularity of its predecessor, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' already had an established fanbase anticipating its release.<ref name=IGNWiiRev/><ref name=EGM100/> The game received critical acclaim, accumulating an aggregate score of 88% on [[GameRankings]] based on eight reviews.<ref name=gr/> The improvements to the gameplay in comparison to its predecessor were praised. ''[[GamePro]]'' commented that \"Sonic 2's game play mechanics are the same as Sonic 1's with a few cool exceptions.\" They gave it a 4.5 out of 5 for sound and a perfect 5.0 in every other category (graphics, control, and fun factor).<ref name=GProrev>{{cite journal |title=Pro Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |author=The Unknown Gamer |journal=GamePro |publisher=IDG |issue=42 |date=January 1993 |pages=46\u201347 |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/5/54/GamePro_US_042.pdf}}</ref> Lucas Thomas of [[IGN]] proclaimed that the game \"offered more of everything. More characters, more levels. More music, moves and baddies to beat\", and that the new spin dash move \"enhanced the speed of the gameplay, as Sonic no longer had to have a long stretch of straightaway to get up to his signature blazing velocity any more.\"<ref name=IGNWiiRev/> Ellie Gibson of ''[[Eurogamer]]'', reviewing the Xbox Live Arcade port, wrote that \"SEGA has been sensible enough to leave things alone. All the original levels are present and correct. They are as expansive and exciting as ever. The sheer speed of the game still has the power to thrill as you send Sonic zooming, spinning and bouncing in all directions.\"<ref name=EuroGRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |last=Gibson |first=Ellie |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=September 17, 2007 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Frank Provo of ''[[GameSpot]]'' wrote \"Play through it and you'll understand why it helped sell a ton of Genesis consoles back in the day. It's a fun platformer and does everything a sequel is supposed to do. It resolves many of the first game's shortcomings and incorporates a slew of minor upgrades that cumulatively amount to a fresh experience.\"<ref name=GSpotWiiRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6172587/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' (Wii) Review |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |date=June 15, 2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> Justin Towell of ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' called the sequel \"an improvement in every respect\", citing the \"improved Special Stage with pseudo-3D shenanigans, a greater emphasis on speed, better graphics, [and] another incredible soundtrack\" as examples.<ref name=GamesRadarRev>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sonics-2d-classics-re-reviewed/5/?page=5 |title=''Sonic'''s 2D classics re-reviewed |last=Towell |first=Justin |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=April 16, 2008 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Tom East of ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' called the game \"arguably the best game in the series and easily one of the best platform games ever\".<ref name=ONMRev/> The main objects of criticism were the two-player mode and the inclusion of the character Tails; reviewers disliked the image distortion brought about by the squeezed and flickering graphics,<ref name=IGNWiiRev/><ref name=GamesRadarRev/><ref name=GProrev/> and Tails was considered to be \"useless\" and \"irritating\" due to his interference in boss battles.<ref name=EuroGRev/><ref name=GamesRadarRev/> By contrast, ''GamePro'' described Tails as \"about the cutest companion that any Sonic fan could ask for\" and said the game's biggest problem is that it is too easy, to the point where even unskilled players would quickly breeze through it. However, the reviewer noted that finding each stage's secrets provides the game with challenge and longevity.<ref name=GProrev/>\n\nCritics praised the game's level design and graphics. ''GamePro'' assessed that the \"graphics are actually better than the original's. The rich variety of scenery, slightly larger sprites, and extra-added attitude help the spunky hedgehog paint video game magic.\"<ref name=GProrev/> Gibson called the variation in the game's environments \"impressive\",<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> and Andy Eddy of ''[[TeamXbox]]'' described the graphics as \"bright\" and \"colorful\".<ref name=\"TeamXboxRev\">{{cite web |url=http://reviews.teamxbox.com/xbox-360/1382/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/p1/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521073319/http://reviews.teamxbox.com/xbox-360/1382/Sonic-The-Hedgehog-2/p1/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review (Xbox 360) |last=Eddy |first=Andy |work=[[TeamXbox]] |date=September 18, 2007 |archivedate=May 21, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Despite the reduction in the number of acts per level to two from the first game's three, the levels themselves were said to be larger and more memorable.<ref name=GProrev/><ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/><ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2007/09/12/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review-2 |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=November 22, 2019 |date=September 12, 2007 |first=Craddock |last=David |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=Ziff Davis}}</ref> Provo pointed out that \"Sega concocted new backgrounds in the same colorful style as those from the first game, then jazzed them up with animated highlights such as dancing flowers and shimmering lakes.\"<ref name=\"GSpotWiiRev\"/> However, the later stages were considered to be difficult and complex.<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/><ref name=\"TeamXboxRev\"/> Towell also noted that \"When Sonic is hurtling around the screen, [the game] could be criticized for 'playing itself'\".<ref name=\"GamesRadarRev\"/> Opinions on the special stages were divided. Gibson described the visuals of these stages as \"dreadfully blocky\",<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> and David Craddock of IGN felt that the inclusion of Tails in the stages was \"detrimental at best, since he's always colliding with bombs, thus causing the player to lose valuable rings.\"<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/> However, those who spoke positively of the special stages approved of the visual effects.<ref name=GProrev/><ref name=MMSegaRev>{{cite magazine|title=Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' |magazine=[[Mean Machines Sega]] |date=November 1992 |issue=2 |pages=60\u20133 |url=http://info.sonicretro.org/Review_-_Sonic_the_Hedgehog_2_%28Mean_Machines_Sega,_November_1992%29 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=GamesRadarRev/> ''GamePro'' elaborated, \"Theoretically, the Genesis isn't capable of scaling, but Sonic's Bonus Rounds are gonna make you wonder!\"<ref name=GProrev/>\n\nSubsequent re-releases also saw positive reviews.<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_360\"/> Thomas wrote that the Virtual Console version was \"an easy thumbs-up\".<ref name=\"IGNWiiRev\"/> The Xbox Live Arcade version's low selling price and the availability of an online mode attracted Gibson's attention: \"It's also much cheaper. Just GBP 4.25 will buy you hours of fun. Not millions of hours, because games were shorter in those days.\"<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Craddock proclaimed that \"''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' holds up as not only one of the best games available on Sega's memorable 16-bit machine, but also a worthy addition to any XBLA library.\"<ref name=\"IGNX360Rev\"/> The iOS version was met with middling reviews,<ref name=\"mc_sonic2_ios\"/> with criticism focused on the subpar quality of the port and lack of multiplayer.<ref name=\"IGNiPhoneRev\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-iphone-171311.phtml |title=Review: ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' iPhone |last=Sterling |first=Jim |date=April 19, 2010 |website=Destructoid |accessdate=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' had sold over 6 million copies,<ref name=\"Gamasutra\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/130268/a_detailed_crossexamination_of_.php?page=2 |title=A Detailed Cross-Examination of Yesterday and Today's Best-Selling Platform Games |page=5 |accessdate=2019-01-28 |date=2006-08-04 |first=Daniel |last=Boutros |work=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> making it the [[List of best-selling video games#Sega Mega Drive/Genesis|second best-selling game for the Sega Genesis]] (after the original ''Sonic the Hedgehog''). The game was a bestseller in the UK charts for 2 months.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Mega |issue=6 |date=March 1993 |title=Official Gallup UK Mega Drive Sales Chart}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' named it the best Genesis game of 1992,<ref name=\"egmbuyersguide1993\">{{cite magazine |year=1993 |title=Buyer's Guide: Best Game of the Year (Genesis) |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |volume= |issue= |id= |quote=Sega's famous mascot -- Sonic the Hedgehog is back for his second visit to the Genesis, and this version is hot! With 8 megabits of memory good ol' Sonic has a lot more room to do cool tricks and this is what makes this version stand head and shoulders above all the other Genesis games that came out this year. All in all, Sonic 2 is the best Genesis cart to come along in a long time!}}</ref> and number 71 on their 1997 list of the best console video games of all time. While they said that ''Sonic CD'' (ranked at number 17) was unquestionably better, they defended the multiplayer mode, contending that \"Although it looks a little squashed, the vs. races are a lot of fun.\"<ref name=EGM100>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=114}} Note: Contrary to the title, the intro to the article explicitly states that the list covers console video games only, meaning PC games and arcade games were not eligible.</ref> ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]'' placed the game at #36 in their \"Top Sega Mega Drive Games of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]|issue=26|page=74|publisher=[[Maverick Magazines]]|date=November 1994}}</ref> In 2000, ''[[Game Informer]]'' ranked ''Sonic 2'' number 61 on its \"Top 100 Games of All Time\" list, calling it \"the most challenging and finely polished ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' title.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |date=August 2001 |title=Top 100 Games of All Time |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |volume=11 |issue=100 |page=28}}</ref> In 2010, ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' took first place in the results of a survey conducted by ''[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]'' to determine the fan-favorite game in the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/17169/features/your-best-sonic-games/?page=3 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009040750/http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/17169/features/your-best-sonic-games/?page=3 |title=Nintendo Feature: Your Best ''Sonic'' games |last=East |first=Thomas |work=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]] |date=May 15, 2010 |archivedate=October 9, 2014 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> In 2011, GameZone named ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' the second-best title in the series (behind ''Sonic the Hedgehog 3'').<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamezone.com/editorials/top_10_sonic_games_of_all_time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207060329/http://www.gamezone.com/editorials/top_10_sonic_games_of_all_time |title=Top 10 ''Sonic'' Games of All Time |last=Sanchez |first=David |work=GameZone |date=July 7, 2011 |archivedate=December 7, 2011 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> In 2017, ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' named ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' the best ''Sonic'' title of all time and the second-best Genesis title of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-sonic-games/3/ |title=The best ''Sonic'' games of all time |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=May 19, 2017 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-sega-genesis-games-all-time/5/ |title=Best Sega Genesis/Mega Drive games of all time |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=June 21, 2017 |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Sonic 2''{{'}}s success was a major factor in Sega catching up to Nintendo in the early-1990s console wars.<ref name=consolewars>{{cite web|last1=Claiborn|first1=Samuel|title=21 Crazy Facts About Sonic And The Console War He Started|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2014/06/26/21-crazy-facts-about-sonic-and-the-console-war-he-started|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It brought their market share up to 40% within six months of its release.<ref name=\"GSRev\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sonic-the-hedgehog-2-review/1900-6178735/ |title=''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' Review |accessdate=2007-10-21 |year=2007 |last=Provo |first=Frank |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> Tails, whom ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2'' introduced, went on to become one of the most prominent characters in the series, appearing as Sonic's sidekick in most ''Sonic'' media, including in later games such as ''[[Sonic Colors]]'', ''[[Sonic Generations]]'', and ''[[Sonic Lost World]]''. ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2''{{'}}s popularity extended to various merchandise such as comic books such as ''[[Sonic the Comic]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ogrecave.com/interviews/jameswallis.shtml |title=Interviews: James Wallis |author=Allan Sugarbaker |date=24 September 2001 |work=OgreCave.com |publisher= |accessdate=22 January 2012|quote=I teamed up with Carl Sargent and Marc Gascoigne to produce four more Sonic books, novels this time, for Virgin Publishing, under the pseudonym of 'Martin Adams'.}}</ref> a [[Sonic the Hedgehog (TV series)|television series]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/KidVid/public/report/19/report.faces?id=56800|title=FCC 398 Children's Television Programming Report|date=March 24, 2005|work=Licensing.FCC.gov|accessdate=7 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315233607/http://licensing.fcc.gov/KidVid/public/report/19/report.faces?id=56800|archivedate=March 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and a sequel, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'', which received similar acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic the Hedgehog 3|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586472-sonic-the-hedgehog-3/index.html|publisher=GameRankings|accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor Sonic's 20th anniversary, Sega released ''Sonic Generations'', which [[Video game remake|remade]] aspects of various past games from the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonic Generations overview|url=http://uk.ign.com/games/sonic-generations/pc-119890|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> The PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, and PC versions contained a remade \"Chemical Plant\" level.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kollar|first1=Phil|title=See Sonic's Classic Chemical Plant Zone From Two Perspectives|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sonic_generations/b/ps3/archive/2011/08/08/see-sonic-39-s-classic-chemical-plant-zone-from-two-perspectives.aspx|website=[[Game Informer]]|publisher=GameStop|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> It also contained a remake of the final boss fight, the Death Egg Robot, as the Classic Era boss of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=NYCC 11: Death Egg Robot Boss|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/6lfx0a/sonic-generations-nycc-11--death-egg-robot-boss-walkthrough|website=[[GameTrailers]]|publisher=DFY Media|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> Separately, the [[Nintendo 3DS]] version of the game contained a remake of the \"Casino Night\" level.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=James|title=Sonic Generations Shots Show Casino Night Action|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2011/09/sonic_generations_shots_show_casino_night_action|website=NintendoLife|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> A \"Casino Night\" themed [[pinball]] minigame was made available for download as a pre-order bonus for the console versions at [[GameStop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Good|first1=Owen|title=Sonic's Casino Night Pinball Comes to PC on Dec. 26|url=http://kotaku.com/5866163/sonics-casino-night-pinball-comes-to-pc-on-dec-26/|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|accessdate=2014-11-16}}</ref> Remade versions of Chemical Plant and Oil Ocean also appear in the 2017 game ''[[Sonic Mania]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Kat|title=Sonic Mania Brings Back the Best Sonic Level Ever|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/sonic-mania-brings-back-the-best-sonic-level-ever|website=USgamer|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD}}In 2008, an unofficial, high-definition remake was announced titled ''Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD'', which included development members who would later work on ''Sonic Mania''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://kotaku.com/5050852/sonic-2-hd-tech-demo-released-requires-serious-blast-processing | title=Sonic 2 HD tech demo released, requires serious blast processing | publisher=Kotaku | date=16 September 2008 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=McWhertor, Micheal}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PagodaWestGames |number=759174613146345472 |date=July 29, 2016 |title=Jared and Tom, formerly a part of S2HD are in charge of level design/art and @teelopesmusic is doing the music.}}</ref> In 2012, it was reported that a potential [[keylogger]] was included with an alpha build of the game, which led to the project being discontinued due to the controversy.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://kotaku.com/5900549/sonic-2-hd-contains-keylogger-delete-immediately | title=Sonic 2 HD contains keylogger, delete immediately | publisher=Kotaku | date=10 April 2012 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Plunkett, Luke}}</ref> In 2014, the project was restarted under a new development team.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/06/29/fan-crafted-sonic-2-hd-project-pokes-its-nose-out-once-more/ | title=Fan-crafted Sonic 2 HD project pokes its nose out once more | publisher=[[Engadget]] | date=6 June 2017 | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Prell, S}}</ref> The final version is planned to feature additional stages and the option to play levels as [[Knuckles the Echidna]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/24/5837612/the-sonic-the-hedgehog-2-hd-fan-project-is-back-from-the-dead | title=The Sonic the Hedgehog 2 HD fan project is back from the dead (correction) | website=Polygon | accessdate=9 October 2017 | author=Ray Corriea, Alexa}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vc.sega.jp/vc_sonic2/ Official Sega webpage] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/Ep8oLkJXWlgKpLFfuEve8Gb_qEWumasV Official Nintendo webpage]\n\n{{Sonic the Hedgehog}}\n{{Sonic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Video games|Japan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonic The Hedgehog 2 (16-Bit)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega Technical Institute games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Sonic Team games]]\n[[Category:Sonic the Hedgehog video games]]\n[[Category:Tiger handheld games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games with expansion packs]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:a281:8e00:2da6:ac72:1b55:6ca6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_the_Hedgehog_2"}
{"title_page": "My Husband's Lover", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 Philippine television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = My Husband's Lover\n| image = My Husband's Lover title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card\n| genre = {{plainlist|\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Romance film|Romance]]}}\n| runtime = 30-45 minutes\n| creator = [[Suzette Doctolero]]\n| creative_director = [[Jun Lana]]\n| director = [[Dominic Zapata]]\n| executive_producer = Carolyn B. Galve\n| writer = {{plainlist|\n* Marlon Miguel\n* Geng Delgado\n* Jason Lim\n* Jonathan Cruz\n* Michelle Amog}}\n| cinematography = Roman Theodossis\n| starring = {{Plain list|\n* [[Dennis Trillo]]\n* [[Tom Rodriguez]]\n* [[Carla Abellana]]}}\n| theme_music_composer = {{plainlist|\n* Cecile Azarcon\n* Tata Betita}}\n| opentheme = \"One More Try\" (instrumental)\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| location = {{plainlist|\n* [[Quezon City]], Philippines\n* [[Subic, Zambales]], Philippines}}\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| company = GMA Entertainment TV\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|2013|6|10}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|2013|10|18}}\n| num_episodes = 94\n| website = http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/tv/my_husbands_lover\n}}\n\n'''''My Husband's Lover''''' is a 2013 [[Philippine television drama]] romance series broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. The series is the first gay themed drama series in Philippine television. Directed by [[Dominic Zapata]], it stars [[Dennis Trillo]] in the title role, [[Tom Rodriguez]] and [[Carla Abellana]]. It premiered on June 10, 2013 on the network's Telebabad line up replacing ''[[Love & Lies]]'' and on June 11, 2013 worldwide on [[GMA Pinoy TV]]. The series concluded on October 18, 2013, with a total of 94 episodes.\n\nThe series is streaming online on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLGRhcC_vtOrbpclfrNOl11PqnV8Vd0fTV |title=My Husband's Lover (Full Episodes) - YouTube |accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nVincent Soriano gets his girlfriend Lally pregnant while they were still in college. They marry and raise a family. While Vincent keeps a secret from his wife, he is gay. When Vincent's former male lover, Eric returns to his life, they have an affair until Lally catches them.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/tv/my_husbands_lover/about/ |title=My Husband's Lover |accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{Main|List of My Husband's Lover characters}}\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Shake, Rattle and Roll XV Official Trailer - Dennis Trillo.jpg\n|caption1 = Dennis Trillo portrays Eric del Mundo.\n|width1 = 150\n|image2 = Carla Abellana, 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|caption2 = Carla Abellana portrays Lally Agatep-Soriano.\n|width2 = 150\n|image3 = Kuh Ledesma Philippine Pop Jazz Singer Commons.jpg\n|caption3 = Kuh Ledesma portrays Elaine Soriano.\n|width3 = 150\n}}\n\n<!--Official cast billing from GMA Network.-->\n;Lead cast\n* [[Dennis Trillo]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Eric Del Mundo|Eric del Mundo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/gma/articles/2013-05-15/8628/Dennis-Trillo-paninindigan-ang-pagiging-bading|title=Dennis Trillo, paninindigan ang pagiging gay|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=May 15, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Rodriguez]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Vincent Soriano|Vincent Soriano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38670/dennis-trillo-and-tom-rodriguez-play-gay-lovers-in-new-kapuso-soap-pledge-loyalty-to-popoy-caritativo|title=Dennis Trillo and Tom Rodriguez play gay lovers in new Kapuso soap; pledge loyalty to Popoy Caritativo|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=May 15, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224101624/http://www.pep.ph/news/38670/dennis-trillo-and-tom-rodriguez-play-gay-lovers-in-new-kapuso-soap-pledge-loyalty-to-popoy-caritativo|archive-date=December 24, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38967/tom-rodriguez-says-role-in-my-husband39s-lover-opened-his-eyes-about-the-plight-of-closet-gays|title=Tom Rodriguez says role in My Husband's Lover opened his eyes about the plight of closet gays|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Carla Abellana]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Lally Agatep-Soriano|Lally Agatep-Soriano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/50010-carla-to-star-in-my-husbands-lover|title=Carla to star in 'My Husband's Lover'|publisher=Journal Online|date=May 9, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623075943/http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/50010-carla-to-star-in-my-husbands-lover|archivedate=June 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38962/carla-abellana-prefers-to-be-cheated-with-another-woman-than-with-a-man|title=Carla Abellana prefers to be cheated with another woman than with a man|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 5, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Supporting cast\n* [[Pancho Magno]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Paul Salcedo|Paul Salcedo]]\n* [[Bettina Carlos]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Vicky Araneta|Vicky Araneta]]<ref name=\"Bettina\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38937/bettina-carlos-on-working-again-with-dennis-trillo-in-my-husbandrsquos-lover-may-pag-asa-na-akong-pagnasaan-nang-kaunti-si-dennisrdquo|title=Bettina Carlos on working again with Dennis Trillo in My Husband's Lover: \"May pag-asa na akong pagnasaan nang kaunti si Dennis!\"|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 5, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Karel Marquez]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Evelyn Agatep|Evelyn Agatep]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/shows/myhusbandslover/videos/2013-06-06/23718/Not-Seen-on-TV-An-invite-from-Karel-Marquez|title=Not Seen on TV: An invite from Karel Marquez|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Santos]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Danny|Danny]]\n* [[Victor Basa]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#David|David]]<ref name=\"Victor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/39013/victor-basa-on-his-respect-for-gays-ldquokapag-tinrato-mo-ang-isang-tao-with-respect-yoursquoll-get-respect-backrdquo|title=Victor Basa on his respect for gays: \"Kapag tinrato mo ang isang tao with respect, you\u2019ll get respect back.\"|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Freeman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-entertainment/2013/06/07/951210/victor-basa-gay-my-husbands-lover|title=Victor Basa is gay in \"My Husband\u2019s Lover\"|publisher=[[The Freeman (newspaper)|The Freeman]]|date=June 7, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Glydel Mercado]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Sandra Agatep|Sandra Agatep]]\n* [[Chanda Romero]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Soledad \"Sol\" Del Mundo|Sol del Mundo]]\n* [[Roi Vinzon]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Armando Soriano|Armando Soriano]]\n* [[Kuh Ledesma]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Elaine Soriano|Elaine Soriano]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38959/kuh-ledesma-on-charice39s-revelation-it-is-best-na-yung-mga-ganoong-bagay-hindi-muna-sabihin|title=Kuh Ledesma on Charice's revelation: \"It is best na yung mga ganoong bagay, hindi muna sabihin.\"|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 4, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tempo.com.ph/2013/06/kuh-wala-pang-balak-mag-retire/#.UbVmo-eqksc|title=Kuh wala pang balak mag-retire|publisher=Tempo|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055530/http://www.tempo.com.ph/2013/06/kuh-wala-pang-balak-mag-retire/#.UbVmo-eqksc#.UbVmo-eqksc|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Recurring cast\n* Antone Limgenco as Diego \"Diegs\" Soriano\n* Elijah Alejo as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Diego and Hanna Soriano|Hanna \"Munchkin\" Soriano]]\n\n;Guest cast\n* [[Keempee de Leon]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Zandro \"Zsa Zsa\" Soriano|Zandro \"Zsa Zsa\" Soriano]]\n* [[Rodjun Cruz]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Martin Lizada|Martin Lizada]]\n* [[Roy Alvarez]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Manuel Soriano|Manuel Soriano]]\n* [[Mark Gil]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Galo Agatep|Galo Agatep]]\n* [[Chynna Ortaleza]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Stella|Stella]]\n* [[Ashley Cabrera]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Mikaella|Mikaella]]\n* [[Jaclyn Jose]] as [[List of Mundo Mo'y Akin characters#Do\u00f1a Charito Vda. de Carbonel|Charito Vda. de Carbonel]]\n* [[Ryan Agoncillo]] as [[List of My Husband's Lover characters#Sam|Sam]]\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Conception and development ===\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin-left:1em; margin-right:2em; font-size:95%; width:28em; max-width:40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"I'm sure a lot of people are gonna say a thing or two about the show. All I really have to say is, this show is a love story. And love is a beautiful thing and it shines through no matter age, no matter race, no matter color, and no matter gender preference. Love is love and no matter what package it comes in, it's still beautiful.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Series' director, Dominic Zapata on the show's theme<ref name= \"PEPphotos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/photos/3826/carla-abellana-tom-rodriguez-and-dennis-trillo-topbill-my-husband39s-lover|title=Carla Abellana, Tom Rodriguez, and Dennis Trillo topbill My Husband's Lover|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 5, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n|}\nSeries' creator [[Suzette Doctolero]] began developing the series in early 2013. It all started with her desire to create a non-traditional, out of the box yet has social relevance, truthful, emotional and with \"real\" characters stories. The idea for the series was conceived when Doctolero began thinking about the question: \"What would you do if you find out that you husband is cheating on you... with another man?\" Although the idea is not-an-easy-story-to-tell because of its controversial theme which touches on the sensitive issue of [[Homosexuality|homosexual]] and [[Bisexuality|bisexual]] relationships, Doctolero explained that \"the show is not all about the queerness of the characters but more of a love story and a family drama. When Doctolero presented the idea to [[GMA Network]], the management said \"yes\" easily because they found the concept interesting and \"it was based on the relatability of the masses to the topic.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/gay-themed-tv-series-my-husbands-lover-gma-network-101705251.html|title=Is the Philippines ready for a gay-themed daily series?|publisher=[[Yahoo!|Yahoo! Philippines]]|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCarolyn Galve served as the executive producer of the series throughout its run. [[Dominic Zapata]] was assigned to direct the show. Zapata said \"It's very refreshing for me to direct this material. The subject is really sensitive and I want to be accurate in portraying how gay people are and the dynamics of gay relationships so we did a lot of research. I don't want to make a mistake or make a misrepresentation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbiz-portal.com/2013/06/my-husbands-lover-first-teleserye-to.html|title='My Husband's Lover' The First Teleserye To Seriously Tackle Homosexual Relationships|publisher=Showbiz Portal|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> Regarding the theme, Zapata stressed \"I'm sure a lot of people are gonna say a thing or two about the show. All I really have to say is, this show is a love story. And love is a beautiful thing and it shines through no matter age, no matter race, no matter color, and no matter gender preference. Love is love and no matter what package it comes in, it's still beautiful.\"<ref name= \"PEPphotos\" />\n\nFilming for the series began May 21, 2013. Many of the scenes were filmed on location in [[Quezon City]]. The show is designed for sixteen-week run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/34566-my-husbands-lover-behind-the-story|title=My Husband\u2019s Lover: Behind the story|publisher=Rappler|date=July 23, 2013|accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> The show is extended for additional three weeks and concluded in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/39940/carla-abellana-returns-to-work-after-hospital-confinement-my-husband39s-lover-to-end-in-october|title=Carla Abellana returns to work after hospital confinement; My Husband's Lover to end in October|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=August 13, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe series' program manager, Helen Rose Sese clarified that the show won't delve on the sensual aspects of relationships\u2014straight or not. \"The show's intention is not to promote gay and lesbian relationship, but more of a reflection that this is happening now. The creative team will also be under scrutiny to try and avoid noise on the part of religious groups. We also make sure we don\u2019t go beyond anything that will offend them, as well as the gay community.\" Sese also stressed that the network has informed the local censors' body on the potentially controversial series. The [[Movie and Television Review and Classification Board]] (MTRCB) has shown understanding of their material while warning them to observe certain limitations in presenting delicate scenes for general viewership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tempo.com.ph/2013/05/gma-tests-market-thru-gay-themed-soap/#.UbAhTtKqksc|title=GMA tests market thru gay-themed soap|publisher=Tempo|date=May 11, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606200321/http://www.tempo.com.ph/2013/05/gma-tests-market-thru-gay-themed-soap/#.UbAhTtKqksc|archive-date=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The show has been approved without cuts by the MTRCB, albeit with an SPG or Strong Parental Guidance rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/show/14754-with-my-husband-s-lover-gma-pushes-the-prime-time-envelope|title=With \u2018My Husband\u2019s Lover,\u2019 GMA pushes the prime-time envelope|publisher=[[BusinessMirror]]|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719191315/http://businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/show/14754-with-my-husband-s-lover-gma-pushes-the-prime-time-envelope#|archive-date=July 19, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA kissing scene between Tom Rodriguez and Dennis Trillo was supposed to be aired in the finale but was not shown due to MTRCB guidelines. The scene could be seen in the DVD version of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/40784/tom-rodriguez-disappointed-over-non-airing-of-kissing-scene-with-dennis-trillo-in-my-husband39s-lover|title=Tom Rodriguez disappointed over non-airing of kissing scene with Dennis Trillo in My Husband's Lover|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nThe series featured three main characters and nine prominent recurring characters throughout its run. [[Dennis Trillo]] and [[Carla Abellana]] were the first two actors to be cast for the lead roles. Abellana was cast as Lally Agatep-Soriano, a woman who struggles to be the perfect wife for the husband she loves who, in fact is a closeted gay. Although she described the series as \"a risky project\",<ref name=\"Carla\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/38581/carla-abellana-finally-stars-in-new-teleserye-after-nine-months-of-waiting|title=Carla Abellana finally stars in new teleserye after nine months of waiting|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=May 8, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> Abellana didn't have qualms accepting the role. She loves that the series encompasses a wider audience which include straight, gay, lesbian, married or single audience. Trillo, on the other hand had recently finishing Temptation of Wife, was chosen to play Eric del Mundo, a gay architect and the lover of Lally\u2019s husband, Vincent Soriano. Trillo was originally cast as Vincent Soriano but he decided to play Eric del Mundo instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X3ETyzhW2Js|title=Kapuso Mo Jessica Soho-My Husband's Lover TomDen June 23, 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=June 23, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> Trillo is not new to gay roles. He already played gay characters in the past \u2013 most particularly in 2004 period film ''[[Aishite Imasu 1941: Mahal Kita]]'' where he won and was nominated in several acting awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manunuri.com/28th_gawad_urian_nominees_2005|title=28th Gawad Urian Nominees (2005)|publisher=[[Gawad Urian Award|Manunuri ng Pelikulang Pilipino]]|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1387739/awards|title=Dennis Trillo - Awards|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Tom Rodriguez]] was chosen to portray Vincent Soriano, a closeted gay, from many actors who auditioned for the said role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/16058/Tom_Rodriguez_is_100%25_sure_of_his_sexuality#.UbSMBOeqksc|title=Tom Rodriguez is 100% sure of his sexuality|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=June 7, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615141701/http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/16058/Tom_Rodriguez_is_100%25_sure_of_his_sexuality#.UbSMBOeqksc#.UbSMBOeqksc|archive-date=June 15, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rodriguez had to go through tests before being cast. He recently left ABS-CBN and signed GMA Network to appear in the show. During his audition, Rodriguez acted one scene\u2014a break-up scene\u2014with Trillo. Zapata described Rodriguez as \"the perfect Vincent\" among the many actors who auditioned for the role, said that \"[While] the others treated homosexuality as a disease, Tom interpreted it with so much understanding, and that's what we're looking for.\" Rodriguez described his role as very complex and demanding as the whole conflict of the show lies in his character. Rodriguez said, to prepare for the project, he watched gay-themed films like ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'' and ''[[Love of Siam]]'' and talked to people with similar stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/98425/tom-rodriguez-not-homophobic|title=Tom Rodriguez \u2018not homophobic\u2019|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=June 13, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> He also did research and found out that \"homosexual love is not really different from a heterosexual one. But of course things are more difficult for them because of all the social biases that exist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/51854-truths-about-stars-that-should-be-kept-private|title=Truths about stars that should be kept private|publisher=Journal|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610084545/http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/51854-truths-about-stars-that-should-be-kept-private|archivedate=June 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSinger [[Kuh Ledesma]] was signed on to portray Elaine Soriano, after reading the week 1 script. The role Armando Soriano was originally offered to [[Phillip Salvador]] but he turned it down, so the role went to [[Roi Vinzon]]. [[Bettina Carlos]] was signed on to play \"the young cougar\" Vicky Araneta, and said that \"My role is seemingly simple but it's a challenge to make the cougar come out and give life to a young cougar.\"<ref name=\"Bettina\" /> [[Victor Basa]] originally auditioned for the role of Vincent Soriano, but ended up portraying David, Vincent's all-out gayfriend and ex-lover.<ref name=\"Carla\" /> Basa finds his role quite difficult in the sense that he doesn't want his character to look \"stereotype\" or just like any other homosexual role seen in media.\n\n== Music ==\nThe main theme song of ''My Husband's Lover'' is \"One More Try\" by [[Kuh Ledesma]], who also portrays Elaine Soriano in the show. This song is also  heard in the opening and ending credits of the show. The song was written by well-known composer [[:tl:Cecile Azarcon|Cecile Azarcon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philmusicregistry.net/main/song/view/2955|title=Philippine Music Registry: \"One More Try\"|publisher=Organisasyon ng Pilipinong Mang-aawit|accessdate=July 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623100206/http://www.philmusicregistry.net/main/song/view/2955|archive-date=June 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was released in 1984 and part of the album ''I Think I'm in Love'' and under the now-defunct Blackgold Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuhledesma.net/kuh_discography.html|title=Kuh Ledesma Discography|publisher=Kuh Ledesma Official Website|date=|accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe secondary theme song, \"Help Me Get Over\" by [[Jonalyn Viray]] and was written by Tata Betita.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdbaby.com/cd/jonalynviray|title=cdbaby: Jonalyn Viray EP|publisher=[[cdbaby]]|date=|accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> It is taken out from ''Jonalyn Viray EP'' which was released in May 19, 2013. The EP was produced by Creative Media Entertainment and distributed by [[Universal Records (Philippines)|Universal Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ph/album/jonalyn-viray-ep/id650280135|title=iTunes: Jonalyn Viray EP|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=|accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOther songs \"Sabihin Mo Naman\" and \"Ayoko Na\" were sung by [[Kris Lawrence]] and composed by himself and Noah Zuniga.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cVeptOLceYgIt|title=Sabihin Mo Naman Official Music Video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> It was the first single of his third album ''Spread the Love''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/records/articles/2013-06-10/30/Spread-the-Love-with-Kris-Lawrence|title=\u2018Spread the Love\u2019 with Kris Lawrence|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=June 10, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> While \"Ayoko Na\", by [[Jessa Zaragoza]] is composed by her husband, [[Dingdong Avanzado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GQ99nLUUVlI|title=Ayoko Na Official Music Video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=August 11, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> It is the third single from her album ''Pag Wala Na Ang Ulan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/guide/10563/jessa-zaragoza-releases-new-album-pag-wala-na-ang-ulan-talks-about-family-life|title=Jessa Zaragoza releases new album, Pag Wala Na Ang Ulan; talks about family life|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=July 19, 2012|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\nAccording to [[AGB Nielsen Philippines]]' Mega Manila household television ratings, the pilot episode of ''My Husband's Lover'' earned a 22.8% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/agb/12109/agb-nielsen-mega-manila-household-ratings-june-10-to-16-2013-ina-kapatid-anak-final-episode-tops-pri |title=AGB Nielsen Mega Manila Household Ratings (June 10 to 16, 2013): Ina Kapatid Anak final episode tops primetime; Sunday All Stars beats rival program on pilot episode |author=Tuazon, Nikko |date=June 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref> While the final episode scored a 25.3% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/agb/12792/agb-nielsen-mega-manila-household-ratings-october-14-to-20-2013-genesis-enters-top-10-my-husband39s-|title=AGB Nielsen Mega Manila Household Ratings (October 14 to 20, 2013): Genesis enters top 10; My Husband's Lover's finale beats Bukas Na Lang Kita Mamahalin |author=Tuazon, Nikko |date=October 29, 2013 |accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe series garnered a positive response from professional critics, noting network's move in producing an \"out-of-the-box\" television series.<ref name=\"netizens\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/312422/showbiz/netizens-rave-over-my-husband-s-lover-pilot-episode|title=Netizens rave over 'My Husband\u2019s Lover' pilot episode|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=June 11, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The show was featured on June 17, 2013 issue of UK-based [[LGBT]] global news website ''[[Gay Star News]]''. It noted that the first episode of ''My Husband's Lover'' for its \"mature, nuanced and honest depiction of gay characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/gay-tv-drama-creates-buzz-philippines170613|title=Gay TV drama creates buzz in the Philippines|publisher=[[Gay Star News]]|date=June 17, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/17793/#.UcBp3ueqksc|title='My Husband\u2019s Lover' cited by international LGBT news site|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=June 18, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622131358/http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/17793#.UcBp3ueqksc|archive-date=June 22, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn his review, Walden Sadiri M. Belen of ''[[Manila Bulletin]]'' responded well to the story, the ensemble's performances, and the director, said that \"the story, unconventional and provocative as it is, was treated beautifully and convincingly. The subject matter \u2014 a married man and a father having an affair with another man \u2014 could  be controversial considering the relatively conservative nature of Filipinos, but so far the series have been decent in presentation and treatment which is fast-paced too. And most noticeable was the remarkable portrayal of the main cast in their respective roles [...]. They are credible in their performances, and especially noted was [[Tom Rodriguez]]'s portrayal of a closet gay who is, ironically, the son of an army general. But all the other members of the cast also delivered A-1 performances: [[Kuh Ledesma]], [[Victor Basa]], [[Glydel Mercado]] and [[Karel Marquez]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/16966/Praises_heaped_on_cast_of_#.UblUXOeqksc|title=Praises heaped on cast of 'My Husband's Lover'|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=June 13, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617024818/http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/16966/Praises_heaped_on_cast_of_#.UblUXOeqksc|archive-date=June 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Radio and TV personality and ''Manila Bulletin'' columnist [[Mr. Fu]] praised the show and its cast, said that \"the show was beautiful, moving, interesting and promising. It has very interesting characters played by credible actors [...]. [[Carla Abellana]], for one, is able to make audiences feel her love for her mother and husband in the story. She has this very fresh television presence, that you would love to watch her every now and then. Dennis [Trillo] has already proven his acting talent and he does not fail on this show. A best example of a cute \"gay who is not so gay\", he knows when to use his eyes, his mouth, his whole body to portray the \"gayness\". Tom, on the other hand, can portray that \"paminta\" (closeted gay) character with confidence, and charm that makes him appealing on screen. Their on-cam chemistry also makes them effective in their roles. The way they trade lines is believable and their body language seems very natural. Their \"revolving glass door\" scene where they accidentally meet after years of not communicating was so romantic and intense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/18018/The_new_love_team_to_beat%C2%A0#.UcKQgueqksc|title=The new love team to beat|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627080417/http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/18018/The_new_love_team_to_beat%C2%A0#.UcKQgueqksc|archive-date=June 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Journal''{{'}}s resident entertainment columnist Butch Roldan also reserved high praise for the show, said that \"the series explains in a broad spectrum that love cannot be defined by sexual preference alone, that love has its own understanding of what is right and wrong and is ready to suffer even under very harsh circumstances.\"<ref name=\"Journal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/52107-understanding-and-accepting-gay-relationships|title=Understanding and accepting gay relationships|publisher=Journal|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613133300/http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/52107-understanding-and-accepting-gay-relationships|archive-date=June 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>''Journal''{{'}}s entertainment columnist, Mario Bautista gave it a mixed review, said that \"The series should have started in the thick of things, since the title and the trailers have already shown where the story is going. Dennis [Trillo] should have been there from the start and then they just go back to how the story all started.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/52199-toni-the-oldest-but-has-longest-relationship|title=Toni the oldest but has longest relationship|publisher=Journal|date=June 13, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616072805/http://www.journal.com.ph/index.php/entertainment/showbiz-news/52199-toni-the-oldest-but-has-longest-relationship|archive-date=June 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTelevision and film director [[Jose Javier Reyes]] congratulated the network \"for taking a risk & giving a fresh take on the tired templates of the telenovelas for something new.\"<ref name=\"netizens\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/39465/Joey-Reyes-commends-GMA-7-for-taking-risk-on-My-Husbands-Lover|title=Joey Reyes commends GMA-7 for taking risk on My Husband's Lover|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin-left:1em; margin-right:2em; font-size:95%; width:28em; max-width:40%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"It feels like a lot of brainpower went into the preparation of the show. Some elements are borderline meticulous, like choosing to add a variety of gay characters to battle the gay stereotype head-on.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014 Mark Angelo Ching, PEP<ref name=\"COMMENTARY: My Husband's Lover\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/12113/commentary-my-husband39s-lover|title=COMMENTARY: My Husband's Lover|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|date=June 22, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n[[LGBT]] advocate and the author of \"Of God and Men: A Life in the Closet\", Atty. Raymond Alikpala reviewed \"GMA Network deserves congratulations for daring to go down this road less travelled. Eschewing the stereotypical storylines and cardboard clich\u00e9 characters, the writers of ''My Husband's Lover'' are depicting homosexual persons as no different from heterosexuals, which is radical in these parts. Homosexual characters have long been television staples, but they have been limited to supporting roles and comic relief. The series' non-stereotypical depiction of gay men can accomplish what [[Ladlad]] failed to do, which is to bring LGBT awareness into the mainstream of Filipino consciousness. Positive media depictions of LGBT persons are crucial in encouraging greater acceptance and recognition of our fundamental equality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/312925/lifestyle/reviews/my-husband-s-lover-where-gays-are-not-clich-eacute-s|title='My Husband\u2019s Lover,' where gays are not clich\u00e9s|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=June 14, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAllan Diones of ''[[Abante Tonite]]'' said that \"[[Dennis Trillo]] and Tom Rodriguez has good screen chemistry [and] they are both excellent actors and can feel the emotions of their characters.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abante-tonite.com/issue/june1713/showbiz_others01.htm#.UcBlzdg7tla|title=Pamhintambalang TomDen, nakakakilig!|publisher=[[Abante Tonite|Abante-Tonite]]|date=June 17, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622054423/http://www.abante-tonite.com/issue/june1713/showbiz_others01.htm#.UcBlzdg7tla|archive-date=June 22, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]'''s Mark Angelo Ching praised [[Suzette Doctolero]] and [[Dominic Zapata]] for \"how the show looks polished. It feels like a lot of brainpower went into the preparation of the show. Some elements are borderline meticulous, like choosing to add a variety of gay characters to battle the gay stereotype head-on.\" He even added that \"unlike other shows that only depicts homosexual men as lustful beasts, or as sidekicks in crass, laughable situations, ''My Husband's Lover'' shows its gay characters in normal, everyday situations: going to the gym, working in an office, or relaxing at home. The characters have successful lives not as beauticians or stand-up comedians, but as architects and businessmen.\" Closing the review, he further added that the show \"is progressive\u2014a unique creation in today\u2019s media landscape where gay men are mostly relegated as sidekicks who provide comic relief. Let\u2019s hope that MHL continues to present homosexuals far from their clich\u00e9 images on television.\"<ref name=\"COMMENTARY: My Husband's Lover\"/>\n\nThe show is under the scrutiny of the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] - Episcopal Commission on Youth (CBCP-ECY) according to its  executive secretary, Father Conegundo Garganta. He added that television producers and writers should study themes being shown to the viewers, especially to the younger ones, and should be based on moral standards. In response to the CBCP statement, the [[Malaca\u00f1ang]] and [[MTRCB]] urged viewers to report any complaints about the show if they saw any unacceptable content against its SPG rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/32114-my-husbands-lover-cbcp-govt|title='My Husband's Lover' under CBCP scrutiny|publisher=Rappler|date=June 25, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The [[GMA Network]] responded that they would continue to comply with MTRCB policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/entertainment/32241-gma-my-husbands-lover|title=GMA-7 defends 'My Husband's Lover'|publisher=Rappler|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe show even impacted the [[Philippine politics]]. On July 19, the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]] held a \"mock\" session for the new representatives which was about investigating the possible ending of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/318298/showbiz/chikaminute/ending-ng-my-husband-s-lover-iimbestigahan-ng-kongreso|title=Ending ng 'My Husband's Lover,' iimbestigahan ng Kongreso?|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=July 19, 2013|accessdate=July 20, 2013}}</ref> On August 8, 2013, [[Legislative districts of Albay|Albay - 1st District]] representative [[Edcel Lagman]] filed the House Bill 2352 in the [[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]]. He called it the ''My Husband's Lover'' bill which seeks to expand the scope of Article 333 of the [[Revised Penal Code of the Philippines|Revised Penal Code]] which only imposes punishment for a spouse having a sexual intercourse to another person of the opposite sex, other than their husband/wife. With this bill, it will add same-sex [[adultery]] to provide equality in the society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/321162/news/nation/my-husband-s-lover-bill-seeks-to-punish-same-sex-adultery|title='My Husband's Lover' bill seeks to punish same-sex adultery|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=August 8, 2013|accessdate=August 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/35954-lagman-same-sex-adultery-bill|title='My Husband's Lover' bill: Penalize same-sex adultery|publisher=Rappler|date=August 8, 2013|accessdate=August 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 2013\n| [[White Party]] Manila / Malate Business Association\n| Plaque of Appreciation\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''My Husband's Lover''\n| {{Won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/315420/showbiz/my-husband-s-lover-kinilala-ng-lgbt-community-sa-white-party-manila|title='My Husband's Lover,' kinilala ng LGBT community sa White Party Manila|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|date=July 1, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |[[27th PMPC Star Awards for Television]]\n| Best Primetime Drama Series\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twitlonger.com/show/n_1rrb848 |title=NOMINEES 27th PMPC Star Awards for Television |publisher=Twitlonger |date=November 8, 2013 |accessdate=November 8, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Drama Actress\n| [[Carla Abellana]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Drama Actor\n| [[Dennis Trillo]]{{hr}}[[Tom Rodriguez]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Drama Supporting Actress\n| [[Glydel Mercado]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Drama Supporting Actor\n| [[Roi Vinzon]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\" | 2014\n| 12th Gawad Tanglaw Awards\n| Best Ensemble Performance (TV Series)\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''My Husband's Lover''\n| {{Won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/01/11/14/abs-cbn-wins-big-12th-gawad-tanglaw|title=Winners for 12th Gawad Tanglaw Awards|publisher=Abs-cbn|date=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 5th Golden Screen TV Awards\n| Outstanding Original Drama Program\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"7\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/guide/13387/golden-screen-tv-awards-nominees-revealednora-aunor-to-receive-lifetime-achievement-award-for-drama |title=Golden Screen TV Awards nominees revealed; Nora Aunor to receive Lifetime Achievement Award for Drama |publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]] |date=February 12, 2014 |accessdate=February 15, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223062147/http://www.pep.ph/guide/guide/13387/golden-screen-tv-awards-nominees-revealednora-aunor-to-receive-lifetime-achievement-award-for-drama|archive-date=February 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Performance by an Actress in a Drama Series\n| Carla Abellana\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Outstanding Performance by an Actor in a Drama Series\n| Dennis Trillo\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Tom Rodriguez\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Program\n| Glydel Mercado\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Program\n| [[Kevin Santos]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Roi Vinzon\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| row