date=October 14, 2013|accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref> It was broadcast in television by GMA Network on October 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/330734/showbiz/mhl-one-more-try-concert-mapapanood-sa-snbo-sa-oktubre-20|title='MHL: One More Try Concert' mapapanood sa SNBO sa Oktubre 20 |publisher=[[GMA Network]] |date=October 13, 2013 |accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref> According to [[AGB Nielsen Philippines]]' Mega Manila household ratings, the television broadcast of ''One More Try: My Husband's Lover The Concert'' earned an 11.9% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/12792/agb-nielsen-mega-manila-household-ratings-october-14-to-20-2013-genesis-enters-top-10-my-husband39s- |title=AGB Nielsen Mega Manila Household Ratings (October 14 to 20, 2013): Genesis enters top 10; My Husband's Lover's finale beats Bukas Na Lang Kita Mamahalin |author=Tuazon, Nikko |date=October 29, 2013 |accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/tv/my_husbands_lover}}\n* {{IMDb title|2973256}}\n\n{{GMA Network (current and upcoming original programming)}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network drama series]]\n[[Category:Philippine LGBT-related television shows]]\n[[Category:Philippine drama television series]]\n[[Category:2013 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2013 Philippine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related drama television series]]\n", "name_user": "Hotwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccolades:fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Husband%27s_Lover"}
{"title_page": "Key (instrument)", "text_new": "{{For|the music theory concept|Key (music)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Steinway Schriftzug.jpg|thumb|right|Keys of a grand piano]]\n[[File:Clarinette auriculaire droit.jpg|thumb|right|Details of a B-flat clarinet: keys for the little finger of the right hand.]]\n\n\n\nWith other instruments, [[zither]]s and [[drum]]s, for example, a key is essentially a small wrench used to turn a tuning machine or lug.\n\nOn [[woodwind]] instruments such as a [[flute]] or [[saxophone]], keys are finger operated levers used to open or close [[tone hole]]s, thereby shortening or lengthening the resonating tube of the instrument. The keys on the keyboard of a [[pipe organ]] also open and close vari\n\n==See also==\n*[[Musical keyboard]]\n*[[Piano key frequencies]]\n\n{{Musical keyboards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Key (Instrument)}}\n[[Category:Human\u2013machine interaction]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument parts and accessories]]\n\n\n{{Musical-instrument-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the music theory concept|Key (music)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Steinway Schriftzug.jpg|thumb|right|Keys of a grand piano]]\n[[File:Clarinette auriculaire droit.jpg|thumb|right|Details of a B-flat clarinet: keys for the little finger of the right hand.]]\n\nA '''key''' is a specific part of a [[musical instrument]]. The purpose and function of the part in question depend on the instrument.\n\nOn instruments equipped with tuning machines such as [[guitar]]s or [[mandolin]]s, a key is part of a [[tuning machine]]. It is a worm gear with a key shaped end used to turn a cog, which, in turn, is attached to a post which winds the string. The key is used to make pitch adjustments to a string.\n\nWith other instruments, [[zither]]s and [[drum]]s, for example, a key is essentially a small wrench used to turn a tuning machine or lug.\n\nOn [[woodwind]] instruments such as a [[flute]] or [[saxophone]], keys are finger operated levers used to open or close [[tone hole]]s, thereby shortening or lengthening the resonating tube of the instrument. The keys on the keyboard of a [[pipe organ]] also open and close various valves, but the airflow is driven mechanically rather than lung powered, and the flow of air is directed through different pipes tuned for each note. The keys of an [[accordion]] direct the air flow from  manually operated [[bellows]] across various tuned vibrating reeds.\n\nOn other [[keyboard instrument]]s, a key may be a lever which mechanically triggers a hammer to strike a group of strings, as on a [[piano]], or an [[electric switch]] which energizes an [[audio oscillator]] as on an [[electronic organ]] or a [[synthesizer]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Musical keyboard]]\n*[[Piano key frequencies]]\n\n{{Musical keyboards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Key (Instrument)}}\n[[Category:Human\u2013machine interaction]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument parts and accessories]]\n\n\n{{Musical-instrument-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2601:582:4800:4870:b11a:1077:575f:6294", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_(instrument)"}
